17/* Support type attribute cache */
18
19/* The cache can keep references to the names alive for longer than
20 they normally would. This is why the maximum size is limited to
21 MCACHE_MAX_ATTR_SIZE, since it might be a problem if very large
22 strings are used as attribute names. */
23#define MCACHE_MAX_ATTR_SIZE 100
24#define MCACHE_SIZE_EXP 12
25#define MCACHE_HASH(version, name_hash) \
26 (((unsigned int)(version) ^ (unsigned int)(name_hash)) \
27 & ((1 << MCACHE_SIZE_EXP) - 1))
28
29#define MCACHE_HASH_METHOD(type, name) \
30 MCACHE_HASH((type)->tp_version_tag, \
31 ((PyASCIIObject *)(name))->hash)
32#define MCACHE_CACHEABLE_NAME(name) \
33 PyUnicode_CheckExact(name) && \
34 PyUnicode_READY(name) != -1 && \
35 PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(name) <= MCACHE_MAX_ATTR_SIZE
36
37struct method_cache_entry {
38 unsigned int version;
39 PyObject *name; /* reference to exactly a str or None */
40 PyObject *value; /* borrowed */
41};
42
43static struct method_cache_entry method_cache[1 << MCACHE_SIZE_EXP];
44static unsigned int next_version_tag = 0;
45
46#define MCACHE_STATS 0
47
48#if MCACHE_STATS
49static size_t method_cache_hits = 0;
50static size_t method_cache_misses = 0;
51static size_t method_cache_collisions = 0;
52#endif

78/*
79 * finds the beginning of the docstring's introspection signature.
80 * if present, returns a pointer pointing to the first '('.
81 * otherwise returns NULL.
82 *
83 * doesn't guarantee that the signature is valid, only that it
84 * has a valid prefix. (the signature must also pass skip_signature.)
85 */
86static const char *
87find_signature(const char *name, const char *doc)
88{
89 const char *dot;
90 size_t length;
91
92 if (!doc)
93 return NULL;
94
95 assert(name != NULL);
96
97 /* for dotted names like classes, only use the last component */
98 dot = strrchr(name, '.');
99 if (dot)
100 name = dot + 1;
101
102 length = strlen(name);
103 if (strncmp(doc, name, length))
104 return NULL;
105 doc += length;
106 if (*doc != '(')
107 return NULL;
108 return doc;
109}
110
111#define SIGNATURE_END_MARKER ")\n--\n\n"
112#define SIGNATURE_END_MARKER_LENGTH 6
113/*
114 * skips past the end of the docstring's instrospection signature.
115 * (assumes doc starts with a valid signature prefix.)
116 */
117static const char *
118skip_signature(const char *doc)
119{
120 while (*doc) {
121 if ((*doc == *SIGNATURE_END_MARKER) &&
122 !strncmp(doc, SIGNATURE_END_MARKER, SIGNATURE_END_MARKER_LENGTH))
123 return doc + SIGNATURE_END_MARKER_LENGTH;
124 if ((*doc == '\n') && (doc[1] == '\n'))
125 return NULL;
126 doc++;
127 }
128 return NULL;
129}

131#ifndef NDEBUG
132static int
133_PyType_CheckConsistency(PyTypeObject *type)
134{
135 if (!(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_READY)) {
136 /* don't check types before PyType_Ready() */
137 return 1;
138 }
139
140 assert(!(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_READYING));
141 assert(type->tp_mro != NULL && PyTuple_Check(type->tp_mro));
142 assert(type->tp_dict != NULL);
143 return 1;
144}
145#endif

147static const char *
148_PyType_DocWithoutSignature(const char *name, const char *internal_doc)
149{
150 const char *doc = find_signature(name, internal_doc);
151
152 if (doc) {
153 doc = skip_signature(doc);
154 if (doc)
155 return doc;
156 }
157 return internal_doc;
158}
159
160PyObject *
161_PyType_GetDocFromInternalDoc(const char *name, const char *internal_doc)
162{
163 const char *doc = _PyType_DocWithoutSignature(name, internal_doc);
164
165 if (!doc || *doc == '\0') {
166 Py_RETURN_NONE;
167 }
168
169 return PyUnicode_FromString(doc);
170}
171
172PyObject *
173_PyType_GetTextSignatureFromInternalDoc(const char *name, const char *internal_doc)
174{
175 const char *start = find_signature(name, internal_doc);
176 const char *end;
177
178 if (start)
179 end = skip_signature(start);
180 else
181 end = NULL;
182 if (!end) {
183 Py_RETURN_NONE;
184 }
185
186 /* back "end" up until it points just past the final ')' */
187 end -= SIGNATURE_END_MARKER_LENGTH - 1;
188 assert((end - start) >= 2); /* should be "()" at least */
189 assert(end[-1] == ')');
190 assert(end[0] == '\n');
191 return PyUnicode_FromStringAndSize(start, end - start);
192}

194unsigned int
195PyType_ClearCache(void)
196{
197 Py_ssize_t i;
198 unsigned int cur_version_tag = next_version_tag - 1;
199
200#if MCACHE_STATS
201 size_t total = method_cache_hits + method_cache_collisions + method_cache_misses;
202 fprintf(stderr, "-- Method cache hits = %zd (%d%%)\n",
203 method_cache_hits, (int) (100.0 * method_cache_hits / total));
204 fprintf(stderr, "-- Method cache true misses = %zd (%d%%)\n",
205 method_cache_misses, (int) (100.0 * method_cache_misses / total));
206 fprintf(stderr, "-- Method cache collisions = %zd (%d%%)\n",
207 method_cache_collisions, (int) (100.0 * method_cache_collisions / total));
208 fprintf(stderr, "-- Method cache size = %zd KB\n",
209 sizeof(method_cache) / 1024);
210#endif
211
212 for (i = 0; i < (1 << MCACHE_SIZE_EXP); i++) {
213 method_cache[i].version = 0;
214 Py_CLEAR(method_cache[i].name);
215 method_cache[i].value = NULL;
216 }
217 next_version_tag = 0;
218 /* mark all version tags as invalid */
219 PyType_Modified(&PyBaseObject_Type);
220 return cur_version_tag;
221}

227 clear_slotdefs();
228}

230void
231PyType_Modified(PyTypeObject *type)
232{
233 /* Invalidate any cached data for the specified type and all
234 subclasses. This function is called after the base
235 classes, mro, or attributes of the type are altered.
236
237 Invariants:
238
239 - Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG is never set if
240 Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_VERSION_TAG is not set (e.g. on type
241 objects coming from non-recompiled extension modules)
242
243 - before Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG can be set on a type,
244 it must first be set on all super types.
245
246 This function clears the Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG of a
247 type (so it must first clear it on all subclasses). The
248 tp_version_tag value is meaningless unless this flag is set.
249 We don't assign new version tags eagerly, but only as
250 needed.
251 */
252 PyObject *raw, *ref;
253 Py_ssize_t i;
254
255 if (!PyType_HasFeature(type, Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG))
256 return;
257
258 raw = type->tp_subclasses;
259 if (raw != NULL) {
260 assert(PyDict_CheckExact(raw));
261 i = 0;
262 while (PyDict_Next(raw, &i, NULL, &ref)) {
263 assert(PyWeakref_CheckRef(ref));
264 ref = PyWeakref_GET_OBJECT(ref);
265 if (ref != Py_None) {
266 PyType_Modified((PyTypeObject *)ref);
267 }
268 }
269 }
270 type->tp_flags &= ~Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG;
271}

273static void
274type_mro_modified(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *bases) {
275 /*
276 Check that all base classes or elements of the MRO of type are
277 able to be cached. This function is called after the base
278 classes or mro of the type are altered.
279
280 Unset HAVE_VERSION_TAG and VALID_VERSION_TAG if the type
281 has a custom MRO that includes a type which is not officially
282 super type.
283
284 Called from mro_internal, which will subsequently be called on
285 each subclass when their mro is recursively updated.
286 */
287 Py_ssize_t i, n;
288 int clear = 0;
289
290 if (!PyType_HasFeature(type, Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_VERSION_TAG))
291 return;
292
293 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
294 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
295 PyObject *b = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
296 PyTypeObject *cls;
297
298 assert(PyType_Check(b));
299 cls = (PyTypeObject *)b;
300
301 if (!PyType_HasFeature(cls, Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_VERSION_TAG) ||
302 !PyType_IsSubtype(type, cls)) {
303 clear = 1;
304 break;
305 }
306 }
307
308 if (clear)
309 type->tp_flags &= ~(Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_VERSION_TAG|
310 Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG);
311}

313static int
314assign_version_tag(PyTypeObject *type)
315{
316 /* Ensure that the tp_version_tag is valid and set
317 Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG. To respect the invariant, this
318 must first be done on all super classes. Return 0 if this
319 cannot be done, 1 if Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG.
320 */
321 Py_ssize_t i, n;
322 PyObject *bases;
323
324 if (PyType_HasFeature(type, Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG))
325 return 1;
326 if (!PyType_HasFeature(type, Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_VERSION_TAG))
327 return 0;
328 if (!PyType_HasFeature(type, Py_TPFLAGS_READY))
329 return 0;
330
331 type->tp_version_tag = next_version_tag++;
332 /* for stress-testing: next_version_tag &= 0xFF; */
333
334 if (type->tp_version_tag == 0) {
335 /* wrap-around or just starting Python - clear the whole
336 cache by filling names with references to Py_None.
337 Values are also set to NULL for added protection, as they
338 are borrowed reference */
339 for (i = 0; i < (1 << MCACHE_SIZE_EXP); i++) {
340 method_cache[i].value = NULL;
341 Py_INCREF(Py_None);
342 Py_XSETREF(method_cache[i].name, Py_None);
343 }
344 /* mark all version tags as invalid */
345 PyType_Modified(&PyBaseObject_Type);
346 return 1;
347 }
348 bases = type->tp_bases;
349 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
350 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
351 PyObject *b = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
352 assert(PyType_Check(b));
353 if (!assign_version_tag((PyTypeObject *)b))
354 return 0;
355 }
356 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG;
357 return 1;
358}

374static int
375check_set_special_type_attr(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *value, const char *name)
376{
377 if (!(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)) {
378 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
379 "can't set %s.%s", type->tp_name, name);
380 return 0;
381 }
382 if (!value) {
383 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
384 "can't delete %s.%s", type->tp_name, name);
385 return 0;
386 }
387 return 1;
388}

390static PyObject *
391type_name(PyTypeObject *type, void *context)
392{
393 const char *s;
394
395 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE) {
396 PyHeapTypeObject* et = (PyHeapTypeObject*)type;
397
398 Py_INCREF(et->ht_name);
399 return et->ht_name;
400 }
401 else {
402 s = strrchr(type->tp_name, '.');
403 if (s == NULL)
404 s = type->tp_name;
405 else
406 s++;
407 return PyUnicode_FromString(s);
408 }
409}

424static int
425type_set_name(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *value, void *context)
426{
427 const char *tp_name;
428 Py_ssize_t name_size;
429
430 if (!check_set_special_type_attr(type, value, "__name__"))
431 return -1;
432 if (!PyUnicode_Check(value)) {
433 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
434 "can only assign string to %s.__name__, not '%s'",
435 type->tp_name, Py_TYPE(value)->tp_name);
436 return -1;
437 }
438
439 tp_name = PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize(value, &name_size);
440 if (tp_name == NULL)
441 return -1;
442 if (strlen(tp_name) != (size_t)name_size) {
443 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,
444 "type name must not contain null characters");
445 return -1;
446 }
447
448 type->tp_name = tp_name;
449 Py_INCREF(value);
450 Py_SETREF(((PyHeapTypeObject*)type)->ht_name, value);
451
452 return 0;
453}

475static PyObject *
476type_module(PyTypeObject *type, void *context)
477{
478 PyObject *mod;
479
480 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE) {
481 mod = _PyDict_GetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___module__);
482 if (mod == NULL) {
483 PyErr_Format(PyExc_AttributeError, "__module__");
484 return NULL;
485 }
486 Py_INCREF(mod);
487 }
488 else {
489 const char *s = strrchr(type->tp_name, '.');
490 if (s != NULL) {
491 mod = PyUnicode_FromStringAndSize(
492 type->tp_name, (Py_ssize_t)(s - type->tp_name));
493 if (mod != NULL)
494 PyUnicode_InternInPlace(&mod);
495 }
496 else {
497 mod = _PyUnicode_FromId(&PyId_builtins);
498 Py_XINCREF(mod);
499 }
500 }
501 return mod;
502}

504static int
505type_set_module(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *value, void *context)
506{
507 if (!check_set_special_type_attr(type, value, "__module__"))
508 return -1;
509
510 PyType_Modified(type);
511
512 return _PyDict_SetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___module__, value);
513}

515static PyObject *
516type_abstractmethods(PyTypeObject *type, void *context)
517{
518 PyObject *mod = NULL;
519 /* type itself has an __abstractmethods__ descriptor (this). Don't return
520 that. */
521 if (type != &PyType_Type)
522 mod = _PyDict_GetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___abstractmethods__);
523 if (!mod) {
524 PyObject *message = _PyUnicode_FromId(&PyId___abstractmethods__);
525 if (message)
526 PyErr_SetObject(PyExc_AttributeError, message);
527 return NULL;
528 }
529 Py_INCREF(mod);
530 return mod;
531}

533static int
534type_set_abstractmethods(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *value, void *context)
535{
536 /* __abstractmethods__ should only be set once on a type, in
537 abc.ABCMeta.__new__, so this function doesn't do anything
538 special to update subclasses.
539 */
540 int abstract, res;
541 if (value != NULL) {
542 abstract = PyObject_IsTrue(value);
543 if (abstract < 0)
544 return -1;
545 res = _PyDict_SetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___abstractmethods__, value);
546 }
547 else {
548 abstract = 0;
549 res = _PyDict_DelItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___abstractmethods__);
550 if (res && PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_KeyError)) {
551 PyObject *message = _PyUnicode_FromId(&PyId___abstractmethods__);
552 if (message)
553 PyErr_SetObject(PyExc_AttributeError, message);
554 return -1;
555 }
556 }
557 if (res == 0) {
558 PyType_Modified(type);
559 if (abstract)
560 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_IS_ABSTRACT;
561 else
562 type->tp_flags &= ~Py_TPFLAGS_IS_ABSTRACT;
563 }
564 return res;
565}

590static int
591mro_hierarchy(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *temp)
592{
593 int res;
594 PyObject *new_mro, *old_mro;
595 PyObject *tuple;
596 PyObject *subclasses;
597 Py_ssize_t i, n;
598
599 res = mro_internal(type, &old_mro);
600 if (res <= 0)
601 /* error / reentrance */
602 return res;
603 new_mro = type->tp_mro;
604
605 if (old_mro != NULL)
606 tuple = PyTuple_Pack(3, type, new_mro, old_mro);
607 else
608 tuple = PyTuple_Pack(2, type, new_mro);
609
610 if (tuple != NULL)
611 res = PyList_Append(temp, tuple);
612 else
613 res = -1;
614 Py_XDECREF(tuple);
615
616 if (res < 0) {
617 type->tp_mro = old_mro;
618 Py_DECREF(new_mro);
619 return -1;
620 }
621 Py_XDECREF(old_mro);
622
623 /* Obtain a copy of subclasses list to iterate over.
624
625 Otherwise type->tp_subclasses might be altered
626 in the middle of the loop, for example, through a custom mro(),
627 by invoking type_set_bases on some subclass of the type
628 which in turn calls remove_subclass/add_subclass on this type.
629
630 Finally, this makes things simple avoiding the need to deal
631 with dictionary iterators and weak references.
632 */
633 subclasses = type___subclasses___impl(type);
634 if (subclasses == NULL)
635 return -1;
636 n = PyList_GET_SIZE(subclasses);
637 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
638 PyTypeObject *subclass;
639 subclass = (PyTypeObject *)PyList_GET_ITEM(subclasses, i);
640 res = mro_hierarchy(subclass, temp);
641 if (res < 0)
642 break;
643 }
644 Py_DECREF(subclasses);
645
646 return res;
647}

649static int
650type_set_bases(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *new_bases, void *context)
651{
652 int res = 0;
653 PyObject *temp;
654 PyObject *old_bases;
655 PyTypeObject *new_base, *old_base;
656 Py_ssize_t i;
657
658 if (!check_set_special_type_attr(type, new_bases, "__bases__"))
659 return -1;
660 if (!PyTuple_Check(new_bases)) {
661 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
662 "can only assign tuple to %s.__bases__, not %s",
663 type->tp_name, Py_TYPE(new_bases)->tp_name);
664 return -1;
665 }
666 if (PyTuple_GET_SIZE(new_bases) == 0) {
667 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
668 "can only assign non-empty tuple to %s.__bases__, not ()",
669 type->tp_name);
670 return -1;
671 }
672 for (i = 0; i < PyTuple_GET_SIZE(new_bases); i++) {
673 PyObject *ob;
674 PyTypeObject *base;
675
676 ob = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(new_bases, i);
677 if (!PyType_Check(ob)) {
678 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
679 "%s.__bases__ must be tuple of classes, not '%s'",
680 type->tp_name, Py_TYPE(ob)->tp_name);
681 return -1;
682 }
683
684 base = (PyTypeObject*)ob;
685 if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, type) ||
686 /* In case of reentering here again through a custom mro()
687 the above check is not enough since it relies on
688 base->tp_mro which would gonna be updated inside
689 mro_internal only upon returning from the mro().
690
691 However, base->tp_base has already been assigned (see
692 below), which in turn may cause an inheritance cycle
693 through tp_base chain. And this is definitely
694 not what you want to ever happen. */
695 (base->tp_mro != NULL && type_is_subtype_base_chain(base, type))) {
696
697 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
698 "a __bases__ item causes an inheritance cycle");
699 return -1;
700 }
701 }
702
703 new_base = best_base(new_bases);
704 if (new_base == NULL)
705 return -1;
706
707 if (!compatible_for_assignment(type->tp_base, new_base, "__bases__"))
708 return -1;
709
710 Py_INCREF(new_bases);
711 Py_INCREF(new_base);
712
713 old_bases = type->tp_bases;
714 old_base = type->tp_base;
715
716 type->tp_bases = new_bases;
717 type->tp_base = new_base;
718
719 temp = PyList_New(0);
720 if (temp == NULL)
721 goto bail;
722 if (mro_hierarchy(type, temp) < 0)
723 goto undo;
724 Py_DECREF(temp);
725
726 /* Take no action in case if type->tp_bases has been replaced
727 through reentrance. */
728 if (type->tp_bases == new_bases) {
729 /* any base that was in __bases__ but now isn't, we
730 need to remove |type| from its tp_subclasses.
731 conversely, any class now in __bases__ that wasn't
732 needs to have |type| added to its subclasses. */
733
734 /* for now, sod that: just remove from all old_bases,
735 add to all new_bases */
736 remove_all_subclasses(type, old_bases);
737 res = add_all_subclasses(type, new_bases);
738 update_all_slots(type);
739 }
740
741 Py_DECREF(old_bases);
742 Py_DECREF(old_base);
743
744 assert(_PyType_CheckConsistency(type));
745 return res;
746
747 undo:
748 for (i = PyList_GET_SIZE(temp) - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
749 PyTypeObject *cls;
750 PyObject *new_mro, *old_mro = NULL;
751
752 PyArg_UnpackTuple(PyList_GET_ITEM(temp, i),
753 "", 2, 3, &cls, &new_mro, &old_mro);
754 /* Do not rollback if cls has a newer version of MRO. */
755 if (cls->tp_mro == new_mro) {
756 Py_XINCREF(old_mro);
757 cls->tp_mro = old_mro;
758 Py_DECREF(new_mro);
759 }
760 }
761 Py_DECREF(temp);
762
763 bail:
764 if (type->tp_bases == new_bases) {
765 assert(type->tp_base == new_base);
766
767 type->tp_bases = old_bases;
768 type->tp_base = old_base;
769
770 Py_DECREF(new_bases);
771 Py_DECREF(new_base);
772 }
773 else {
774 Py_DECREF(old_bases);
775 Py_DECREF(old_base);
776 }
777
778 assert(_PyType_CheckConsistency(type));
779 return -1;
780}

874static PyObject *
875type_repr(PyTypeObject *type)
876{
877 PyObject *mod, *name, *rtn;
878
879 mod = type_module(type, NULL);
880 if (mod == NULL)
881 PyErr_Clear();
882 else if (!PyUnicode_Check(mod)) {
883 Py_DECREF(mod);
884 mod = NULL;
885 }
886 name = type_qualname(type, NULL);
887 if (name == NULL) {
888 Py_XDECREF(mod);
889 return NULL;
890 }
891
892 if (mod != NULL && !_PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(mod, &PyId_builtins))
893 rtn = PyUnicode_FromFormat("<class '%U.%U'>", mod, name);
894 else
895 rtn = PyUnicode_FromFormat("<class '%s'>", type->tp_name);
896
897 Py_XDECREF(mod);
898 Py_DECREF(name);
899 return rtn;
900}

902static PyObject *
903type_call(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
904{
905 PyObject *obj;
906
907 if (type->tp_new == NULL) {
908 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
909 "cannot create '%.100s' instances",
910 type->tp_name);
911 return NULL;
912 }
913
914#ifdef Py_DEBUG
915 /* type_call() must not be called with an exception set,
916 because it can clear it (directly or indirectly) and so the
917 caller loses its exception */
918 assert(!PyErr_Occurred());
919#endif
920
921 obj = type->tp_new(type, args, kwds);
922 obj = _Py_CheckFunctionResult((PyObject*)type, obj, NULL);
923 if (obj == NULL)
924 return NULL;
925
926 /* Ugly exception: when the call was type(something),
927 don't call tp_init on the result. */
928 if (type == &PyType_Type &&
929 PyTuple_Check(args) && PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args) == 1 &&
930 (kwds == NULL ||
931 (PyDict_Check(kwds) && PyDict_GET_SIZE(kwds) == 0)))
932 return obj;
933
934 /* If the returned object is not an instance of type,
935 it won't be initialized. */
936 if (!PyType_IsSubtype(Py_TYPE(obj), type))
937 return obj;
938
939 type = Py_TYPE(obj);
940 if (type->tp_init != NULL) {
941 int res = type->tp_init(obj, args, kwds);
942 if (res < 0) {
943 assert(PyErr_Occurred());
944 Py_DECREF(obj);
945 obj = NULL;
946 }
947 else {
948 assert(!PyErr_Occurred());
949 }
950 }
951 return obj;
952}
953
954PyObject *
955PyType_GenericAlloc(PyTypeObject *type, Py_ssize_t nitems)
956{
957 PyObject *obj;
958 const size_t size = _PyObject_VAR_SIZE(type, nitems+1);
959 /* note that we need to add one, for the sentinel */
960
961 if (PyType_IS_GC(type))
962 obj = _PyObject_GC_Malloc(size);
963 else
964 obj = (PyObject *)PyObject_MALLOC(size);
965
966 if (obj == NULL)
967 return PyErr_NoMemory();
968
969 memset(obj, '\0', size);
970
971 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
972 Py_INCREF(type);
973
974 if (type->tp_itemsize == 0)
975 (void)PyObject_INIT(obj, type);
976 else
977 (void) PyObject_INIT_VAR((PyVarObject *)obj, type, nitems);
978
979 if (PyType_IS_GC(type))
980 _PyObject_GC_TRACK(obj);
981 return obj;
982}

984PyObject *
985PyType_GenericNew(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
986{
987 return type->tp_alloc(type, 0);
988}

990/* Helpers for subtyping */
991
992static int
993traverse_slots(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *self, visitproc visit, void *arg)
994{
995 Py_ssize_t i, n;
996 PyMemberDef *mp;
997
998 n = Py_SIZE(type);
999 mp = PyHeapType_GET_MEMBERS((PyHeapTypeObject *)type);
1000 for (i = 0; i < n; i++, mp++) {
1001 if (mp->type == T_OBJECT_EX) {
1002 char *addr = (char *)self + mp->offset;
1003 PyObject *obj = *(PyObject **)addr;
1004 if (obj != NULL) {
1005 int err = visit(obj, arg);
1006 if (err)
1007 return err;
1008 }
1009 }
1010 }
1011 return 0;
1012}
1013
1014static int
1015subtype_traverse(PyObject *self, visitproc visit, void *arg)
1016{
1017 PyTypeObject *type, *base;
1018 traverseproc basetraverse;
1019
1020 /* Find the nearest base with a different tp_traverse,
1021 and traverse slots while we're at it */
1022 type = Py_TYPE(self);
1023 base = type;
1024 while ((basetraverse = base->tp_traverse) == subtype_traverse) {
1025 if (Py_SIZE(base)) {
1026 int err = traverse_slots(base, self, visit, arg);
1027 if (err)
1028 return err;
1029 }
1030 base = base->tp_base;
1031 assert(base);
1032 }
1033
1034 if (type->tp_dictoffset != base->tp_dictoffset) {
1035 PyObject **dictptr = _PyObject_GetDictPtr(self);
1036 if (dictptr && *dictptr)
1037 Py_VISIT(*dictptr);
1038 }
1039
1040 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
1041 /* For a heaptype, the instances count as references
1042 to the type. Traverse the type so the collector
1043 can find cycles involving this link. */
1044 Py_VISIT(type);
1045
1046 if (basetraverse)
1047 return basetraverse(self, visit, arg);
1048 return 0;
1049}
1050
1051static void
1052clear_slots(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *self)
1053{
1054 Py_ssize_t i, n;
1055 PyMemberDef *mp;
1056
1057 n = Py_SIZE(type);
1058 mp = PyHeapType_GET_MEMBERS((PyHeapTypeObject *)type);
1059 for (i = 0; i < n; i++, mp++) {
1060 if (mp->type == T_OBJECT_EX && !(mp->flags & READONLY)) {
1061 char *addr = (char *)self + mp->offset;
1062 PyObject *obj = *(PyObject **)addr;
1063 if (obj != NULL) {
1064 *(PyObject **)addr = NULL;
1065 Py_DECREF(obj);
1066 }
1067 }
1068 }
1069}
1070
1071static int
1072subtype_clear(PyObject *self)
1073{
1074 PyTypeObject *type, *base;
1075 inquiry baseclear;
1076
1077 /* Find the nearest base with a different tp_clear
1078 and clear slots while we're at it */
1079 type = Py_TYPE(self);
1080 base = type;
1081 while ((baseclear = base->tp_clear) == subtype_clear) {
1082 if (Py_SIZE(base))
1083 clear_slots(base, self);
1084 base = base->tp_base;
1085 assert(base);
1086 }
1087
1088 /* Clear the instance dict (if any), to break cycles involving only
1089 __dict__ slots (as in the case 'self.__dict__ is self'). */
1090 if (type->tp_dictoffset != base->tp_dictoffset) {
1091 PyObject **dictptr = _PyObject_GetDictPtr(self);
1092 if (dictptr && *dictptr)
1093 Py_CLEAR(*dictptr);
1094 }
1095
1096 if (baseclear)
1097 return baseclear(self);
1098 return 0;
1099}
1100
1101static void
1102subtype_dealloc(PyObject *self)
1103{
1104 PyTypeObject *type, *base;
1105 destructor basedealloc;
1106 PyThreadState *tstate = PyThreadState_GET();
1107 int has_finalizer;
1108
1109 /* Extract the type; we expect it to be a heap type */
1110 type = Py_TYPE(self);
1111 assert(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE);
1112
1113 /* Test whether the type has GC exactly once */
1114
1115 if (!PyType_IS_GC(type)) {
1116 /* It's really rare to find a dynamic type that doesn't have
1117 GC; it can only happen when deriving from 'object' and not
1118 adding any slots or instance variables. This allows
1119 certain simplifications: there's no need to call
1120 clear_slots(), or DECREF the dict, or clear weakrefs. */
1121
1122 /* Maybe call finalizer; exit early if resurrected */
1123 if (type->tp_finalize) {
1124 if (PyObject_CallFinalizerFromDealloc(self) < 0)
1125 return;
1126 }
1127 if (type->tp_del) {
1128 type->tp_del(self);
1129 if (self->ob_refcnt > 0)
1130 return;
1131 }
1132
1133 /* Find the nearest base with a different tp_dealloc */
1134 base = type;
1135 while ((basedealloc = base->tp_dealloc) == subtype_dealloc) {
1136 assert(Py_SIZE(base) == 0);
1137 base = base->tp_base;
1138 assert(base);
1139 }
1140
1141 /* Extract the type again; tp_del may have changed it */
1142 type = Py_TYPE(self);
1143
1144 /* Call the base tp_dealloc() */
1145 assert(basedealloc);
1146 basedealloc(self);
1147
1148 /* Can't reference self beyond this point */
1149 Py_DECREF(type);
1150
1151 /* Done */
1152 return;
1153 }
1154
1155 /* We get here only if the type has GC */
1156
1157 /* UnTrack and re-Track around the trashcan macro, alas */
1158 /* See explanation at end of function for full disclosure */
1159 PyObject_GC_UnTrack(self);
1160 ++_PyTrash_delete_nesting;
1161 ++ tstate->trash_delete_nesting;
1162 Py_TRASHCAN_SAFE_BEGIN(self);
1163 --_PyTrash_delete_nesting;
1164 -- tstate->trash_delete_nesting;
1165
1166 /* Find the nearest base with a different tp_dealloc */
1167 base = type;
1168 while ((/*basedealloc =*/ base->tp_dealloc) == subtype_dealloc) {
1169 base = base->tp_base;
1170 assert(base);
1171 }
1172
1173 has_finalizer = type->tp_finalize || type->tp_del;
1174
1175 if (type->tp_finalize) {
1176 _PyObject_GC_TRACK(self);
1177 if (PyObject_CallFinalizerFromDealloc(self) < 0) {
1178 /* Resurrected */
1179 goto endlabel;
1180 }
1181 _PyObject_GC_UNTRACK(self);
1182 }
1183 /*
1184 If we added a weaklist, we clear it. Do this *before* calling tp_del,
1185 clearing slots, or clearing the instance dict.
1186
1187 GC tracking must be off at this point. weakref callbacks (if any, and
1188 whether directly here or indirectly in something we call) may trigger GC,
1189 and if self is tracked at that point, it will look like trash to GC and GC
1190 will try to delete self again.
1191 */
1192 if (type->tp_weaklistoffset && !base->tp_weaklistoffset)
1193 PyObject_ClearWeakRefs(self);
1194
1195 if (type->tp_del) {
1196 _PyObject_GC_TRACK(self);
1197 type->tp_del(self);
1198 if (self->ob_refcnt > 0) {
1199 /* Resurrected */
1200 goto endlabel;
1201 }
1202 _PyObject_GC_UNTRACK(self);
1203 }
1204 if (has_finalizer) {
1205 /* New weakrefs could be created during the finalizer call.
1206 If this occurs, clear them out without calling their
1207 finalizers since they might rely on part of the object
1208 being finalized that has already been destroyed. */
1209 if (type->tp_weaklistoffset && !base->tp_weaklistoffset) {
1210 /* Modeled after GET_WEAKREFS_LISTPTR() */
1211 PyWeakReference **list = (PyWeakReference **) \
1212 PyObject_GET_WEAKREFS_LISTPTR(self);
1213 while (*list)
1214 _PyWeakref_ClearRef(*list);
1215 }
1216 }
1217
1218 /* Clear slots up to the nearest base with a different tp_dealloc */
1219 base = type;
1220 while ((basedealloc = base->tp_dealloc) == subtype_dealloc) {
1221 if (Py_SIZE(base))
1222 clear_slots(base, self);
1223 base = base->tp_base;
1224 assert(base);
1225 }
1226
1227 /* If we added a dict, DECREF it */
1228 if (type->tp_dictoffset && !base->tp_dictoffset) {
1229 PyObject **dictptr = _PyObject_GetDictPtr(self);
1230 if (dictptr != NULL) {
1231 PyObject *dict = *dictptr;
1232 if (dict != NULL) {
1233 Py_DECREF(dict);
1234 *dictptr = NULL;
1235 }
1236 }
1237 }
1238
1239 /* Extract the type again; tp_del may have changed it */
1240 type = Py_TYPE(self);
1241
1242 /* Call the base tp_dealloc(); first retrack self if
1243 * basedealloc knows about gc.
1244 */
1245 if (PyType_IS_GC(base))
1246 _PyObject_GC_TRACK(self);
1247 assert(basedealloc);
1248 basedealloc(self);
1249
1250 /* Can't reference self beyond this point. It's possible tp_del switched
1251 our type from a HEAPTYPE to a non-HEAPTYPE, so be careful about
1252 reference counting. */
1253 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
1254 Py_DECREF(type);
1255
1256 endlabel:
1257 ++_PyTrash_delete_nesting;
1258 ++ tstate->trash_delete_nesting;
1259 Py_TRASHCAN_SAFE_END(self);
1260 --_PyTrash_delete_nesting;
1261 -- tstate->trash_delete_nesting;
1262
1263 /* Explanation of the weirdness around the trashcan macros:
1264
1265 Q. What do the trashcan macros do?
1266
1267 A. Read the comment titled "Trashcan mechanism" in object.h.
1268 For one, this explains why there must be a call to GC-untrack
1269 before the trashcan begin macro. Without understanding the
1270 trashcan code, the answers to the following questions don't make
1271 sense.
1272
1273 Q. Why do we GC-untrack before the trashcan and then immediately
1274 GC-track again afterward?
1275
1276 A. In the case that the base class is GC-aware, the base class
1277 probably GC-untracks the object. If it does that using the
1278 UNTRACK macro, this will crash when the object is already
1279 untracked. Because we don't know what the base class does, the
1280 only safe thing is to make sure the object is tracked when we
1281 call the base class dealloc. But... The trashcan begin macro
1282 requires that the object is *untracked* before it is called. So
1283 the dance becomes:
1284
1285 GC untrack
1286 trashcan begin
1287 GC track
1288
1289 Q. Why did the last question say "immediately GC-track again"?
1290 It's nowhere near immediately.
1291
1292 A. Because the code *used* to re-track immediately. Bad Idea.
1293 self has a refcount of 0, and if gc ever gets its hands on it
1294 (which can happen if any weakref callback gets invoked), it
1295 looks like trash to gc too, and gc also tries to delete self
1296 then. But we're already deleting self. Double deallocation is
1297 a subtle disaster.
1298
1299 Q. Why the bizarre (net-zero) manipulation of
1300 _PyTrash_delete_nesting around the trashcan macros?
1301
1302 A. Some base classes (e.g. list) also use the trashcan mechanism.
1303 The following scenario used to be possible:
1304
1305 - suppose the trashcan level is one below the trashcan limit
1306
1307 - subtype_dealloc() is called
1308
1309 - the trashcan limit is not yet reached, so the trashcan level
1310 is incremented and the code between trashcan begin and end is
1311 executed
1312
1313 - this destroys much of the object's contents, including its
1314 slots and __dict__
1315
1316 - basedealloc() is called; this is really list_dealloc(), or
1317 some other type which also uses the trashcan macros
1318
1319 - the trashcan limit is now reached, so the object is put on the
1320 trashcan's to-be-deleted-later list
1321
1322 - basedealloc() returns
1323
1324 - subtype_dealloc() decrefs the object's type
1325
1326 - subtype_dealloc() returns
1327
1328 - later, the trashcan code starts deleting the objects from its
1329 to-be-deleted-later list
1330
1331 - subtype_dealloc() is called *AGAIN* for the same object
1332
1333 - at the very least (if the destroyed slots and __dict__ don't
1334 cause problems) the object's type gets decref'ed a second
1335 time, which is *BAD*!!!
1336
1337 The remedy is to make sure that if the code between trashcan
1338 begin and end in subtype_dealloc() is called, the code between
1339 trashcan begin and end in basedealloc() will also be called.
1340 This is done by decrementing the level after passing into the
1341 trashcan block, and incrementing it just before leaving the
1342 block.
1343
1344 But now it's possible that a chain of objects consisting solely
1345 of objects whose deallocator is subtype_dealloc() will defeat
1346 the trashcan mechanism completely: the decremented level means
1347 that the effective level never reaches the limit. Therefore, we
1348 *increment* the level *before* entering the trashcan block, and
1349 matchingly decrement it after leaving. This means the trashcan
1350 code will trigger a little early, but that's no big deal.
1351
1352 Q. Are there any live examples of code in need of all this
1353 complexity?
1354
1355 A. Yes. See SF bug 668433 for code that crashed (when Python was
1356 compiled in debug mode) before the trashcan level manipulations
1357 were added. For more discussion, see SF patches 581742, 575073
1358 and bug 574207.
1359 */
1360}

1364/* type test with subclassing support */
1365
1366static int
1367type_is_subtype_base_chain(PyTypeObject *a, PyTypeObject *b)
1368{
1369 do {
1370 if (a == b)
1371 return 1;
1372 a = a->tp_base;
1373 } while (a != NULL);
1374
1375 return (b == &PyBaseObject_Type);
1376}
1377
1378int
1379PyType_IsSubtype(PyTypeObject *a, PyTypeObject *b)
1380{
1381 PyObject *mro;
1382
1383 mro = a->tp_mro;
1384 if (mro != NULL) {
1385 /* Deal with multiple inheritance without recursion
1386 by walking the MRO tuple */
1387 Py_ssize_t i, n;
1388 assert(PyTuple_Check(mro));
1389 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(mro);
1390 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
1391 if (PyTuple_GET_ITEM(mro, i) == (PyObject *)b)
1392 return 1;
1393 }
1394 return 0;
1395 }
1396 else
1397 /* a is not completely initilized yet; follow tp_base */
1398 return type_is_subtype_base_chain(a, b);
1399}

1401/* Routines to do a method lookup in the type without looking in the
1402 instance dictionary (so we can't use PyObject_GetAttr) but still
1403 binding it to the instance.
1404
1405 Variants:
1406
1407 - _PyObject_LookupSpecial() returns NULL without raising an exception
1408 when the _PyType_Lookup() call fails;
1409
1410 - lookup_maybe_method() and lookup_method() are internal routines similar
1411 to _PyObject_LookupSpecial(), but can return unbound PyFunction
1412 to avoid temporary method object. Pass self as first argument when
1413 unbound == 1.
1414*/
1415
1416PyObject *
1417_PyObject_LookupSpecial(PyObject *self, _Py_Identifier *attrid)
1418{
1419 PyObject *res;
1420
1421 res = _PyType_LookupId(Py_TYPE(self), attrid);
1422 if (res != NULL) {
1423 descrgetfunc f;
1424 if ((f = Py_TYPE(res)->tp_descr_get) == NULL)
1425 Py_INCREF(res);
1426 else
1427 res = f(res, self, (PyObject *)(Py_TYPE(self)));
1428 }
1429 return res;
1430}
1431
1432static PyObject *
1433lookup_maybe_method(PyObject *self, _Py_Identifier *attrid, int *unbound)
1434{
1435 PyObject *res = _PyType_LookupId(Py_TYPE(self), attrid);
1436 if (res == NULL) {
1437 return NULL;
1438 }
1439
1440 if (PyFunction_Check(res)) {
1441 /* Avoid temporary PyMethodObject */
1442 *unbound = 1;
1443 Py_INCREF(res);
1444 }
1445 else {
1446 *unbound = 0;
1447 descrgetfunc f = Py_TYPE(res)->tp_descr_get;
1448 if (f == NULL) {
1449 Py_INCREF(res);
1450 }
1451 else {
1452 res = f(res, self, (PyObject *)(Py_TYPE(self)));
1453 }
1454 }
1455 return res;
1456}
1457
1458static PyObject *
1459lookup_method(PyObject *self, _Py_Identifier *attrid, int *unbound)
1460{
1461 PyObject *res = lookup_maybe_method(self, attrid, unbound);
1462 if (res == NULL && !PyErr_Occurred()) {
1463 PyErr_SetObject(PyExc_AttributeError, attrid->object);
1464 }
1465 return res;
1466}

1468static PyObject*
1469call_unbound(int unbound, PyObject *func, PyObject *self,
1470 PyObject **args, Py_ssize_t nargs)
1471{
1472 if (unbound) {
1473 return _PyObject_FastCall_Prepend(func, self, args, nargs);
1474 }
1475 else {
1476 return _PyObject_FastCall(func, args, nargs);
1477 }
1478}
1479
1480static PyObject*
1481call_unbound_noarg(int unbound, PyObject *func, PyObject *self)
1482{
1483 if (unbound) {
1484 PyObject *args[1] = {self};
1485 return _PyObject_FastCall(func, args, 1);
1486 }
1487 else {
1488 return _PyObject_CallNoArg(func);
1489 }
1490}

1492/* A variation of PyObject_CallMethod* that uses lookup_maybe_method()
1493 instead of PyObject_GetAttrString(). */
1494static PyObject *
1495call_method(PyObject *obj, _Py_Identifier *name,
1496 PyObject **args, Py_ssize_t nargs)
1497{
1498 int unbound;
1499 PyObject *func, *retval;
1500
1501 func = lookup_method(obj, name, &unbound);
1502 if (func == NULL) {
1503 return NULL;
1504 }
1505 retval = call_unbound(unbound, func, obj, args, nargs);
1506 Py_DECREF(func);
1507 return retval;
1508}
1509
1510/* Clone of call_method() that returns NotImplemented when the lookup fails. */
1511
1512static PyObject *
1513call_maybe(PyObject *obj, _Py_Identifier *name,
1514 PyObject **args, Py_ssize_t nargs)
1515{
1516 int unbound;
1517 PyObject *func, *retval;
1518
1519 func = lookup_maybe_method(obj, name, &unbound);
1520 if (func == NULL) {
1521 if (!PyErr_Occurred())
1522 Py_RETURN_NOTIMPLEMENTED;
1523 return NULL;
1524 }
1525
1526 retval = call_unbound(unbound, func, obj, args, nargs);
1527 Py_DECREF(func);
1528 return retval;
1529}

1531/*
1532 Method resolution order algorithm C3 described in
1533 "A Monotonic Superclass Linearization for Dylan",
1534 by Kim Barrett, Bob Cassel, Paul Haahr,
1535 David A. Moon, Keith Playford, and P. Tucker Withington.
1536 (OOPSLA 1996)
1537
1538 Some notes about the rules implied by C3:
1539
1540 No duplicate bases.
1541 It isn't legal to repeat a class in a list of base classes.
1542
1543 The next three properties are the 3 constraints in "C3".
1544
1545 Local precedence order.
1546 If A precedes B in C's MRO, then A will precede B in the MRO of all
1547 subclasses of C.
1548
1549 Monotonicity.
1550 The MRO of a class must be an extension without reordering of the
1551 MRO of each of its superclasses.
1552
1553 Extended Precedence Graph (EPG).
1554 Linearization is consistent if there is a path in the EPG from
1555 each class to all its successors in the linearization. See
1556 the paper for definition of EPG.
1557 */
1558
1559static int
1560tail_contains(PyObject *list, int whence, PyObject *o) {
1561 Py_ssize_t j, size;
1562 size = PyList_GET_SIZE(list);
1563
1564 for (j = whence+1; j < size; j++) {
1565 if (PyList_GET_ITEM(list, j) == o)
1566 return 1;
1567 }
1568 return 0;
1569}
1570
1571static PyObject *
1572class_name(PyObject *cls)
1573{
1574 PyObject *name = _PyObject_GetAttrId(cls, &PyId___name__);
1575 if (name == NULL) {
1576 PyErr_Clear();
1577 name = PyObject_Repr(cls);
1578 }
1579 if (name == NULL)
1580 return NULL;
1581 if (!PyUnicode_Check(name)) {
1582 Py_DECREF(name);
1583 return NULL;
1584 }
1585 return name;
1586}
1587
1588static int
1589check_duplicates(PyObject *list)
1590{
1591 Py_ssize_t i, j, n;
1592 /* Let's use a quadratic time algorithm,
1593 assuming that the bases lists is short.
1594 */
1595 n = PyList_GET_SIZE(list);
1596 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
1597 PyObject *o = PyList_GET_ITEM(list, i);
1598 for (j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
1599 if (PyList_GET_ITEM(list, j) == o) {
1600 o = class_name(o);
1601 if (o != NULL) {
1602 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
1603 "duplicate base class %U",
1604 o);
1605 Py_DECREF(o);
1606 } else {
1607 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
1608 "duplicate base class");
1609 }
1610 return -1;
1611 }
1612 }
1613 }
1614 return 0;
1615}
1616
1617/* Raise a TypeError for an MRO order disagreement.
1618
1619 It's hard to produce a good error message. In the absence of better
1620 insight into error reporting, report the classes that were candidates
1621 to be put next into the MRO. There is some conflict between the
1622 order in which they should be put in the MRO, but it's hard to
1623 diagnose what constraint can't be satisfied.
1624*/
1625
1626static void
1627set_mro_error(PyObject *to_merge, int *remain)
1628{
1629 Py_ssize_t i, n, off, to_merge_size;
1630 char buf[1000];
1631 PyObject *k, *v;
1632 PyObject *set = PyDict_New();
1633 if (!set) return;
1634
1635 to_merge_size = PyList_GET_SIZE(to_merge);
1636 for (i = 0; i < to_merge_size; i++) {
1637 PyObject *L = PyList_GET_ITEM(to_merge, i);
1638 if (remain[i] < PyList_GET_SIZE(L)) {
1639 PyObject *c = PyList_GET_ITEM(L, remain[i]);
1640 if (PyDict_SetItem(set, c, Py_None) < 0) {
1641 Py_DECREF(set);
1642 return;
1643 }
1644 }
1645 }
1646 n = PyDict_GET_SIZE(set);
1647
1648 off = PyOS_snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "Cannot create a \
1649consistent method resolution\norder (MRO) for bases");
1650 i = 0;
1651 while (PyDict_Next(set, &i, &k, &v) && (size_t)off < sizeof(buf)) {
1652 PyObject *name = class_name(k);
1653 const char *name_str;
1654 if (name != NULL) {
1655 name_str = PyUnicode_AsUTF8(name);
1656 if (name_str == NULL)
1657 name_str = "?";
1658 } else
1659 name_str = "?";
1660 off += PyOS_snprintf(buf + off, sizeof(buf) - off, " %s", name_str);
1661 Py_XDECREF(name);
1662 if (--n && (size_t)(off+1) < sizeof(buf)) {
1663 buf[off++] = ',';
1664 buf[off] = '\0';
1665 }
1666 }
1667 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError, buf);
1668 Py_DECREF(set);
1669}
1670
1671static int
1672pmerge(PyObject *acc, PyObject* to_merge)
1673{
1674 int res = 0;
1675 Py_ssize_t i, j, to_merge_size, empty_cnt;
1676 int *remain;
1677
1678 to_merge_size = PyList_GET_SIZE(to_merge);
1679
1680 /* remain stores an index into each sublist of to_merge.
1681 remain[i] is the index of the next base in to_merge[i]
1682 that is not included in acc.
1683 */
1684 remain = (int *)PyMem_MALLOC(SIZEOF_INT*to_merge_size);
1685 if (remain == NULL) {
1686 PyErr_NoMemory();
1687 return -1;
1688 }
1689 for (i = 0; i < to_merge_size; i++)
1690 remain[i] = 0;
1691
1692 again:
1693 empty_cnt = 0;
1694 for (i = 0; i < to_merge_size; i++) {
1695 PyObject *candidate;
1696
1697 PyObject *cur_list = PyList_GET_ITEM(to_merge, i);
1698
1699 if (remain[i] >= PyList_GET_SIZE(cur_list)) {
1700 empty_cnt++;
1701 continue;
1702 }
1703
1704 /* Choose next candidate for MRO.
1705
1706 The input sequences alone can determine the choice.
1707 If not, choose the class which appears in the MRO
1708 of the earliest direct superclass of the new class.
1709 */
1710
1711 candidate = PyList_GET_ITEM(cur_list, remain[i]);
1712 for (j = 0; j < to_merge_size; j++) {
1713 PyObject *j_lst = PyList_GET_ITEM(to_merge, j);
1714 if (tail_contains(j_lst, remain[j], candidate))
1715 goto skip; /* continue outer loop */
1716 }
1717 res = PyList_Append(acc, candidate);
1718 if (res < 0)
1719 goto out;
1720
1721 for (j = 0; j < to_merge_size; j++) {
1722 PyObject *j_lst = PyList_GET_ITEM(to_merge, j);
1723 if (remain[j] < PyList_GET_SIZE(j_lst) &&
1724 PyList_GET_ITEM(j_lst, remain[j]) == candidate) {
1725 remain[j]++;
1726 }
1727 }
1728 goto again;
1729 skip: ;
1730 }
1731
1732 if (empty_cnt != to_merge_size) {
1733 set_mro_error(to_merge, remain);
1734 res = -1;
1735 }
1736
1737 out:
1738 PyMem_FREE(remain);
1739
1740 return res;
1741}
1742
1743static PyObject *
1744mro_implementation(PyTypeObject *type)
1745{
1746 PyObject *result = NULL;
1747 PyObject *bases;
1748 PyObject *to_merge, *bases_aslist;
1749 int res;
1750 Py_ssize_t i, n;
1751
1752 if (type->tp_dict == NULL) {
1753 if (PyType_Ready(type) < 0)
1754 return NULL;
1755 }
1756
1757 /* Find a superclass linearization that honors the constraints
1758 of the explicit lists of bases and the constraints implied by
1759 each base class.
1760
1761 to_merge is a list of lists, where each list is a superclass
1762 linearization implied by a base class. The last element of
1763 to_merge is the declared list of bases.
1764 */
1765
1766 bases = type->tp_bases;
1767 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
1768
1769 to_merge = PyList_New(n+1);
1770 if (to_merge == NULL)
1771 return NULL;
1772
1773 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
1774 PyTypeObject *base;
1775 PyObject *base_mro_aslist;
1776
1777 base = (PyTypeObject *)PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
1778 if (base->tp_mro == NULL) {
1779 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
1780 "Cannot extend an incomplete type '%.100s'",
1781 base->tp_name);
1782 goto out;
1783 }
1784
1785 base_mro_aslist = PySequence_List(base->tp_mro);
1786 if (base_mro_aslist == NULL)
1787 goto out;
1788
1789 PyList_SET_ITEM(to_merge, i, base_mro_aslist);
1790 }
1791
1792 bases_aslist = PySequence_List(bases);
1793 if (bases_aslist == NULL)
1794 goto out;
1795 /* This is just a basic sanity check. */
1796 if (check_duplicates(bases_aslist) < 0) {
1797 Py_DECREF(bases_aslist);
1798 goto out;
1799 }
1800 PyList_SET_ITEM(to_merge, n, bases_aslist);
1801
1802 result = Py_BuildValue("[O]", (PyObject *)type);
1803 if (result == NULL)
1804 goto out;
1805
1806 res = pmerge(result, to_merge);
1807 if (res < 0)
1808 Py_CLEAR(result);
1809
1810 out:
1811 Py_DECREF(to_merge);
1812
1813 return result;
1814}

1829static int
1830mro_check(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *mro)
1831{
1832 PyTypeObject *solid;
1833 Py_ssize_t i, n;
1834
1835 solid = solid_base(type);
1836
1837 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(mro);
1838 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
1839 PyTypeObject *base;
1840 PyObject *tmp;
1841
1842 tmp = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(mro, i);
1843 if (!PyType_Check(tmp)) {
1844 PyErr_Format(
1845 PyExc_TypeError,
1846 "mro() returned a non-class ('%.500s')",
1847 Py_TYPE(tmp)->tp_name);
1848 return -1;
1849 }
1850
1851 base = (PyTypeObject*)tmp;
1852 if (!PyType_IsSubtype(solid, solid_base(base))) {
1853 PyErr_Format(
1854 PyExc_TypeError,
1855 "mro() returned base with unsuitable layout ('%.500s')",
1856 base->tp_name);
1857 return -1;
1858 }
1859 }
1860
1861 return 0;
1862}
1863
1864/* Lookups an mcls.mro method, invokes it and checks the result (if needed,
1865 in case of a custom mro() implementation).
1866
1867 Keep in mind that during execution of this function type->tp_mro
1868 can be replaced due to possible reentrance (for example,
1869 through type_set_bases):
1870
1871 - when looking up the mcls.mro attribute (it could be
1872 a user-provided descriptor);
1873
1874 - from inside a custom mro() itself;
1875
1876 - through a finalizer of the return value of mro().
1877*/
1878static PyObject *
1879mro_invoke(PyTypeObject *type)
1880{
1881 PyObject *mro_result;
1882 PyObject *new_mro;
1883 int custom = (Py_TYPE(type) != &PyType_Type);
1884
1885 if (custom) {
1886 _Py_IDENTIFIER(mro);
1887 int unbound;
1888 PyObject *mro_meth = lookup_method((PyObject *)type, &PyId_mro,
1889 &unbound);
1890 if (mro_meth == NULL)
1891 return NULL;
1892 mro_result = call_unbound_noarg(unbound, mro_meth, (PyObject *)type);
1893 Py_DECREF(mro_meth);
1894 }
1895 else {
1896 mro_result = mro_implementation(type);
1897 }
1898 if (mro_result == NULL)
1899 return NULL;
1900
1901 new_mro = PySequence_Tuple(mro_result);
1902 Py_DECREF(mro_result);
1903 if (new_mro == NULL)
1904 return NULL;
1905
1906 if (custom && mro_check(type, new_mro) < 0) {
1907 Py_DECREF(new_mro);
1908 return NULL;
1909 }
1910
1911 return new_mro;
1912}
1913
1914/* Calculates and assigns a new MRO to type->tp_mro.
1915 Return values and invariants:
1916
1917 - Returns 1 if a new MRO value has been set to type->tp_mro due to
1918 this call of mro_internal (no tricky reentrancy and no errors).
1919
1920 In case if p_old_mro argument is not NULL, a previous value
1921 of type->tp_mro is put there, and the ownership of this
1922 reference is transferred to a caller.
1923 Otherwise, the previous value (if any) is decref'ed.
1924
1925 - Returns 0 in case when type->tp_mro gets changed because of
1926 reentering here through a custom mro() (see a comment to mro_invoke).
1927
1928 In this case, a refcount of an old type->tp_mro is adjusted
1929 somewhere deeper in the call stack (by the innermost mro_internal
1930 or its caller) and may become zero upon returning from here.
1931 This also implies that the whole hierarchy of subclasses of the type
1932 has seen the new value and updated their MRO accordingly.
1933
1934 - Returns -1 in case of an error.
1935*/
1936static int
1937mro_internal(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject **p_old_mro)
1938{
1939 PyObject *new_mro, *old_mro;
1940 int reent;
1941
1942 /* Keep a reference to be able to do a reentrancy check below.
1943 Don't let old_mro be GC'ed and its address be reused for
1944 another object, like (suddenly!) a new tp_mro. */
1945 old_mro = type->tp_mro;
1946 Py_XINCREF(old_mro);
1947 new_mro = mro_invoke(type); /* might cause reentrance */
1948 reent = (type->tp_mro != old_mro);
1949 Py_XDECREF(old_mro);
1950 if (new_mro == NULL)
1951 return -1;
1952
1953 if (reent) {
1954 Py_DECREF(new_mro);
1955 return 0;
1956 }
1957
1958 type->tp_mro = new_mro;
1959
1960 type_mro_modified(type, type->tp_mro);
1961 /* corner case: the super class might have been hidden
1962 from the custom MRO */
1963 type_mro_modified(type, type->tp_bases);
1964
1965 PyType_Modified(type);
1966
1967 if (p_old_mro != NULL)
1968 *p_old_mro = old_mro; /* transfer the ownership */
1969 else
1970 Py_XDECREF(old_mro);
1971
1972 return 1;
1973}

1976/* Calculate the best base amongst multiple base classes.
1977 This is the first one that's on the path to the "solid base". */
1978
1979static PyTypeObject *
1980best_base(PyObject *bases)
1981{
1982 Py_ssize_t i, n;
1983 PyTypeObject *base, *winner, *candidate, *base_i;
1984 PyObject *base_proto;
1985
1986 assert(PyTuple_Check(bases));
1987 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
1988 assert(n > 0);
1989 base = NULL;
1990 winner = NULL;
1991 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
1992 base_proto = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
1993 if (!PyType_Check(base_proto)) {
1994 PyErr_SetString(
1995 PyExc_TypeError,
1996 "bases must be types");
1997 return NULL;
1998 }
1999 base_i = (PyTypeObject *)base_proto;
2000 if (base_i->tp_dict == NULL) {
2001 if (PyType_Ready(base_i) < 0)
2002 return NULL;
2003 }
2004 if (!PyType_HasFeature(base_i, Py_TPFLAGS_BASETYPE)) {
2005 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2006 "type '%.100s' is not an acceptable base type",
2007 base_i->tp_name);
2008 return NULL;
2009 }
2010 candidate = solid_base(base_i);
2011 if (winner == NULL) {
2012 winner = candidate;
2013 base = base_i;
2014 }
2015 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(winner, candidate))
2016 ;
2017 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(candidate, winner)) {
2018 winner = candidate;
2019 base = base_i;
2020 }
2021 else {
2022 PyErr_SetString(
2023 PyExc_TypeError,
2024 "multiple bases have "
2025 "instance lay-out conflict");
2026 return NULL;
2027 }
2028 }
2029 assert (base != NULL);
2030
2031 return base;
2032}
2033
2034static int
2035extra_ivars(PyTypeObject *type, PyTypeObject *base)
2036{
2037 size_t t_size = type->tp_basicsize;
2038 size_t b_size = base->tp_basicsize;
2039
2040 assert(t_size >= b_size); /* Else type smaller than base! */
2041 if (type->tp_itemsize || base->tp_itemsize) {
2042 /* If itemsize is involved, stricter rules */
2043 return t_size != b_size ||
2044 type->tp_itemsize != base->tp_itemsize;
2045 }
2046 if (type->tp_weaklistoffset && base->tp_weaklistoffset == 0 &&
2047 type->tp_weaklistoffset + sizeof(PyObject *) == t_size &&
2048 type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
2049 t_size -= sizeof(PyObject *);
2050 if (type->tp_dictoffset && base->tp_dictoffset == 0 &&
2051 type->tp_dictoffset + sizeof(PyObject *) == t_size &&
2052 type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
2053 t_size -= sizeof(PyObject *);
2054
2055 return t_size != b_size;
2056}
2057
2058static PyTypeObject *
2059solid_base(PyTypeObject *type)
2060{
2061 PyTypeObject *base;
2062
2063 if (type->tp_base)
2064 base = solid_base(type->tp_base);
2065 else
2066 base = &PyBaseObject_Type;
2067 if (extra_ivars(type, base))
2068 return type;
2069 else
2070 return base;
2071}

2088 while (type->tp_base != NULL) {

2090 !(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE))
2091 return type;
2092 type = type->tp_base;
2093 }
2094 return NULL;

2119{

2131 if (func == NULL) {

2136 }

2141subtype_setdict(PyObject *obj, PyObject *value, void *context)
2142{

2146 base = get_builtin_base_with_dict(Py_TYPE(obj));
2147 if (base != NULL) {
2148 descrsetfunc func;

2155 if (func == NULL) {

2160 }

2165 "This object has no __dict__");
2166 return -1;
2167 }
2168 if (value != NULL && !PyDict_Check(value)) {
2169 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2170 "__dict__ must be set to a dictionary, "
2171 "not a '%.200s'", Py_TYPE(value)->tp_name);
2172 return -1;
2173 }
2174 Py_XINCREF(value);
2175 Py_XSETREF(*dictptr, value);
2176 return 0;
2177}
2178
2179static PyObject *
2180subtype_getweakref(PyObject *obj, void *context)
2181{
2182 PyObject **weaklistptr;
2183 PyObject *result;
2184
2185 if (Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_weaklistoffset == 0) {
2186 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_AttributeError,
2187 "This object has no __weakref__");
2188 return NULL;
2189 }
2190 assert(Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_weaklistoffset > 0);
2191 assert(Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_weaklistoffset + sizeof(PyObject *) <=
2192 (size_t)(Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_basicsize));
2193 weaklistptr = (PyObject **)
2194 ((char *)obj + Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_weaklistoffset);
2195 if (*weaklistptr == NULL)
2196 result = Py_None;
2197 else
2198 result = *weaklistptr;
2199 Py_INCREF(result);
2200 return result;
2201}

2226valid_identifier(PyObject *s)
2227{
2228 if (!PyUnicode_Check(s)) {
2229 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2230 "__slots__ items must be strings, not '%.200s'",
2231 Py_TYPE(s)->tp_name);
2232 return 0;
2233 }

2235 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
2236 "__slots__ must be identifiers");
2237 return 0;

2239 return 1;

2245
2246static int
2247type_init(PyObject *cls, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
2248{
2249 int res;
2250
2251 assert(args != NULL && PyTuple_Check(args));
2252 assert(kwds == NULL || PyDict_Check(kwds));
2253
2254 if (kwds != NULL && PyTuple_Check(args) && PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args) == 1 &&
2255 PyDict_Check(kwds) && PyDict_GET_SIZE(kwds) != 0) {
2256 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
2257 "type.__init__() takes no keyword arguments");
2258 return -1;
2259 }
2260
2261 if (args != NULL && PyTuple_Check(args) &&
2262 (PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args) != 1 && PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args) != 3)) {
2263 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
2264 "type.__init__() takes 1 or 3 arguments");
2265 return -1;
2266 }
2267
2268 /* Call object.__init__(self) now. */
2269 /* XXX Could call super(type, cls).__init__() but what's the point? */
2270 args = PyTuple_GetSlice(args, 0, 0);
2271 res = object_init(cls, args, NULL);
2272 Py_DECREF(args);
2273 return res;
2274}

2281
2282/* Determine the most derived metatype. */
2283PyTypeObject *
2284_PyType_CalculateMetaclass(PyTypeObject *metatype, PyObject *bases)
2285{
2286 Py_ssize_t i, nbases;
2287 PyTypeObject *winner;
2288 PyObject *tmp;
2289 PyTypeObject *tmptype;
2290
2291 /* Determine the proper metatype to deal with this,
2292 and check for metatype conflicts while we're at it.
2293 Note that if some other metatype wins to contract,
2294 it's possible that its instances are not types. */
2295
2296 nbases = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
2297 winner = metatype;
2298 for (i = 0; i < nbases; i++) {
2299 tmp = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
2300 tmptype = Py_TYPE(tmp);
2301 if (PyType_IsSubtype(winner, tmptype))
2302 continue;
2303 if (PyType_IsSubtype(tmptype, winner)) {
2304 winner = tmptype;
2305 continue;
2306 }
2307 /* else: */
2308 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
2309 "metaclass conflict: "
2310 "the metaclass of a derived class "
2311 "must be a (non-strict) subclass "
2312 "of the metaclasses of all its bases");
2313 return NULL;
2314 }
2315 return winner;
2316}
2317
2318static PyObject *
2319type_new(PyTypeObject *metatype, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
2320{
2321 PyObject *name, *bases = NULL, *orig_dict, *dict = NULL;
2322 PyObject *qualname, *slots = NULL, *tmp, *newslots, *cell;
2323 PyTypeObject *type = NULL, *base, *tmptype, *winner;
2324 PyHeapTypeObject *et;
2325 PyMemberDef *mp;
2326 Py_ssize_t i, nbases, nslots, slotoffset, name_size;
2327 int j, may_add_dict, may_add_weak, add_dict, add_weak;
2328 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__qualname__);
2329 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__slots__);
2330 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__classcell__);
2331
2332 assert(args != NULL && PyTuple_Check(args));
2333 assert(kwds == NULL || PyDict_Check(kwds));
2334
2335 /* Special case: type(x) should return x->ob_type */
2336 /* We only want type itself to accept the one-argument form (#27157)
2337 Note: We don't call PyType_CheckExact as that also allows subclasses */
2338 if (metatype == &PyType_Type) {
2339 const Py_ssize_t nargs = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args);
2340 const Py_ssize_t nkwds = kwds == NULL ? 0 : PyDict_GET_SIZE(kwds);
2341
2342 if (nargs == 1 && nkwds == 0) {
2343 PyObject *x = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(args, 0);
2344 Py_INCREF(Py_TYPE(x));
2345 return (PyObject *) Py_TYPE(x);
2346 }
2347
2348 /* SF bug 475327 -- if that didn't trigger, we need 3
2349 arguments. but PyArg_ParseTupleAndKeywords below may give
2350 a msg saying type() needs exactly 3. */
2351 if (nargs != 3) {
2352 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
2353 "type() takes 1 or 3 arguments");
2354 return NULL;
2355 }
2356 }
2357
2358 /* Check arguments: (name, bases, dict) */
2359 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "UO!O!:type.__new__", &name, &PyTuple_Type,
2360 &bases, &PyDict_Type, &orig_dict))
2361 return NULL;
2362
2363 /* Determine the proper metatype to deal with this: */
2364 winner = _PyType_CalculateMetaclass(metatype, bases);
2365 if (winner == NULL) {
2366 return NULL;
2367 }
2368
2369 if (winner != metatype) {
2370 if (winner->tp_new != type_new) /* Pass it to the winner */
2371 return winner->tp_new(winner, args, kwds);
2372 metatype = winner;
2373 }
2374
2375 /* Adjust for empty tuple bases */
2376 nbases = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
2377 if (nbases == 0) {
2378 bases = PyTuple_Pack(1, &PyBaseObject_Type);
2379 if (bases == NULL)
2380 goto error;
2381 nbases = 1;
2382 }
2383 else
2384 Py_INCREF(bases);
2385
2386 /* Calculate best base, and check that all bases are type objects */
2387 base = best_base(bases);
2388 if (base == NULL) {
2389 goto error;
2390 }
2391
2392 dict = PyDict_Copy(orig_dict);
2393 if (dict == NULL)
2394 goto error;
2395
2396 /* Check for a __slots__ sequence variable in dict, and count it */
2397 slots = _PyDict_GetItemId(dict, &PyId___slots__);
2398 nslots = 0;
2399 add_dict = 0;
2400 add_weak = 0;
2401 may_add_dict = base->tp_dictoffset == 0;
2402 may_add_weak = base->tp_weaklistoffset == 0 && base->tp_itemsize == 0;
2403 if (slots == NULL) {
2404 if (may_add_dict) {
2405 add_dict++;
2406 }
2407 if (may_add_weak) {
2408 add_weak++;
2409 }
2410 }
2411 else {
2412 /* Have slots */
2413
2414 /* Make it into a tuple */
2415 if (PyUnicode_Check(slots))
2416 slots = PyTuple_Pack(1, slots);
2417 else
2418 slots = PySequence_Tuple(slots);
2419 if (slots == NULL)
2420 goto error;
2421 assert(PyTuple_Check(slots));
2422
2423 /* Are slots allowed? */
2424 nslots = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(slots);
2425 if (nslots > 0 && base->tp_itemsize != 0) {
2426 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2427 "nonempty __slots__ "
2428 "not supported for subtype of '%s'",
2429 base->tp_name);
2430 goto error;
2431 }
2432
2433 /* Check for valid slot names and two special cases */
2434 for (i = 0; i < nslots; i++) {
2435 PyObject *tmp = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(slots, i);
2436 if (!valid_identifier(tmp))
2437 goto error;
2438 assert(PyUnicode_Check(tmp));
2439 if (_PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(tmp, &PyId___dict__)) {
2440 if (!may_add_dict || add_dict) {
2441 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
2442 "__dict__ slot disallowed: "
2443 "we already got one");
2444 goto error;
2445 }
2446 add_dict++;
2447 }
2448 if (_PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIString(tmp, "__weakref__")) {
2449 if (!may_add_weak || add_weak) {
2450 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
2451 "__weakref__ slot disallowed: "
2452 "either we already got one, "
2453 "or __itemsize__ != 0");
2454 goto error;
2455 }
2456 add_weak++;
2457 }
2458 }
2459
2460 /* Copy slots into a list, mangle names and sort them.
2461 Sorted names are needed for __class__ assignment.
2462 Convert them back to tuple at the end.
2463 */
2464 newslots = PyList_New(nslots - add_dict - add_weak);
2465 if (newslots == NULL)
2466 goto error;
2467 for (i = j = 0; i < nslots; i++) {
2468 tmp = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(slots, i);
2469 if ((add_dict &&
2470 _PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(tmp, &PyId___dict__)) ||
2471 (add_weak &&
2472 _PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIString(tmp, "__weakref__")))
2473 continue;
2474 tmp =_Py_Mangle(name, tmp);
2475 if (!tmp) {
2476 Py_DECREF(newslots);
2477 goto error;
2478 }
2479 PyList_SET_ITEM(newslots, j, tmp);
2480 if (PyDict_GetItem(dict, tmp)) {
2481 /* CPython inserts __qualname__ and __classcell__ (when needed)
2482 into the namespace when creating a class. They will be deleted
2483 below so won't act as class variables. */
2484 if (!_PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(tmp, &PyId___qualname__) &&
2485 !_PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(tmp, &PyId___classcell__)) {
2486 PyErr_Format(PyExc_ValueError,
2487 "%R in __slots__ conflicts with class variable",
2488 tmp);
2489 Py_DECREF(newslots);
2490 goto error;
2491 }
2492 }
2493 j++;
2494 }
2495 assert(j == nslots - add_dict - add_weak);
2496 nslots = j;
2497 Py_CLEAR(slots);
2498 if (PyList_Sort(newslots) == -1) {
2499 Py_DECREF(newslots);
2500 goto error;
2501 }
2502 slots = PyList_AsTuple(newslots);
2503 Py_DECREF(newslots);
2504 if (slots == NULL)
2505 goto error;
2506
2507 /* Secondary bases may provide weakrefs or dict */
2508 if (nbases > 1 &&
2509 ((may_add_dict && !add_dict) ||
2510 (may_add_weak && !add_weak))) {
2511 for (i = 0; i < nbases; i++) {
2512 tmp = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
2513 if (tmp == (PyObject *)base)
2514 continue; /* Skip primary base */
2515 assert(PyType_Check(tmp));
2516 tmptype = (PyTypeObject *)tmp;
2517 if (may_add_dict && !add_dict &&
2518 tmptype->tp_dictoffset != 0)
2519 add_dict++;
2520 if (may_add_weak && !add_weak &&
2521 tmptype->tp_weaklistoffset != 0)
2522 add_weak++;
2523 if (may_add_dict && !add_dict)
2524 continue;
2525 if (may_add_weak && !add_weak)
2526 continue;
2527 /* Nothing more to check */
2528 break;
2529 }
2530 }
2531 }
2532
2533 /* Allocate the type object */
2534 type = (PyTypeObject *)metatype->tp_alloc(metatype, nslots);
2535 if (type == NULL)
2536 goto error;
2537
2538 /* Keep name and slots alive in the extended type object */
2539 et = (PyHeapTypeObject *)type;
2540 Py_INCREF(name);
2541 et->ht_name = name;
2542 et->ht_slots = slots;
2543 slots = NULL;
2544
2545 /* Initialize tp_flags */
2546 type->tp_flags = Py_TPFLAGS_DEFAULT | Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE |
2547 Py_TPFLAGS_BASETYPE | Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_FINALIZE;
2548 if (base->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC)
2549 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC;
2550
2551 /* Initialize essential fields */
2552 type->tp_as_async = &et->as_async;
2553 type->tp_as_number = &et->as_number;
2554 type->tp_as_sequence = &et->as_sequence;
2555 type->tp_as_mapping = &et->as_mapping;
2556 type->tp_as_buffer = &et->as_buffer;
2557 type->tp_name = PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize(name, &name_size);
2558 if (!type->tp_name)
2559 goto error;
2560 if (strlen(type->tp_name) != (size_t)name_size) {
2561 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,
2562 "type name must not contain null characters");
2563 goto error;
2564 }
2565
2566 /* Set tp_base and tp_bases */
2567 type->tp_bases = bases;
2568 bases = NULL;
2569 Py_INCREF(base);
2570 type->tp_base = base;
2571
2572 /* Initialize tp_dict from passed-in dict */
2573 Py_INCREF(dict);
2574 type->tp_dict = dict;
2575
2576 /* Set __module__ in the dict */
2577 if (_PyDict_GetItemId(dict, &PyId___module__) == NULL) {
2578 tmp = PyEval_GetGlobals();
2579 if (tmp != NULL) {
2580 tmp = _PyDict_GetItemId(tmp, &PyId___name__);
2581 if (tmp != NULL) {
2582 if (_PyDict_SetItemId(dict, &PyId___module__,
2583 tmp) < 0)
2584 goto error;
2585 }
2586 }
2587 }
2588
2589 /* Set ht_qualname to dict['__qualname__'] if available, else to
2590 __name__. The __qualname__ accessor will look for ht_qualname.
2591 */
2592 qualname = _PyDict_GetItemId(dict, &PyId___qualname__);
2593 if (qualname != NULL) {
2594 if (!PyUnicode_Check(qualname)) {
2595 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2596 "type __qualname__ must be a str, not %s",
2597 Py_TYPE(qualname)->tp_name);
2598 goto error;
2599 }
2600 }
2601 et->ht_qualname = qualname ? qualname : et->ht_name;
2602 Py_INCREF(et->ht_qualname);
2603 if (qualname != NULL && _PyDict_DelItemId(dict, &PyId___qualname__) < 0)
2604 goto error;
2605
2606 /* Set tp_doc to a copy of dict['__doc__'], if the latter is there
2607 and is a string. The __doc__ accessor will first look for tp_doc;
2608 if that fails, it will still look into __dict__.
2609 */
2610 {
2611 PyObject *doc = _PyDict_GetItemId(dict, &PyId___doc__);
2612 if (doc != NULL && PyUnicode_Check(doc)) {
2613 Py_ssize_t len;
2614 const char *doc_str;
2615 char *tp_doc;
2616
2617 doc_str = PyUnicode_AsUTF8(doc);
2618 if (doc_str == NULL)
2619 goto error;
2620 /* Silently truncate the docstring if it contains null bytes. */
2621 len = strlen(doc_str);
2622 tp_doc = (char *)PyObject_MALLOC(len + 1);
2623 if (tp_doc == NULL) {
2624 PyErr_NoMemory();
2625 goto error;
2626 }
2627 memcpy(tp_doc, doc_str, len + 1);
2628 type->tp_doc = tp_doc;
2629 }
2630 }
2631
2632 /* Special-case __new__: if it's a plain function,
2633 make it a static function */
2634 tmp = _PyDict_GetItemId(dict, &PyId___new__);
2635 if (tmp != NULL && PyFunction_Check(tmp)) {
2636 tmp = PyStaticMethod_New(tmp);
2637 if (tmp == NULL)
2638 goto error;
2639 if (_PyDict_SetItemId(dict, &PyId___new__, tmp) < 0) {
2640 Py_DECREF(tmp);
2641 goto error;
2642 }
2643 Py_DECREF(tmp);
2644 }
2645
2646 /* Special-case __init_subclass__: if it's a plain function,
2647 make it a classmethod */
2648 tmp = _PyDict_GetItemId(dict, &PyId___init_subclass__);
2649 if (tmp != NULL && PyFunction_Check(tmp)) {
2650 tmp = PyClassMethod_New(tmp);
2651 if (tmp == NULL)
2652 goto error;
2653 if (_PyDict_SetItemId(dict, &PyId___init_subclass__, tmp) < 0) {
2654 Py_DECREF(tmp);
2655 goto error;
2656 }
2657 Py_DECREF(tmp);
2658 }
2659
2660 /* Add descriptors for custom slots from __slots__, or for __dict__ */
2661 mp = PyHeapType_GET_MEMBERS(et);
2662 slotoffset = base->tp_basicsize;
2663 if (et->ht_slots != NULL) {
2664 for (i = 0; i < nslots; i++, mp++) {
2665 mp->name = PyUnicode_AsUTF8(
2666 PyTuple_GET_ITEM(et->ht_slots, i));
2667 if (mp->name == NULL)
2668 goto error;
2669 mp->type = T_OBJECT_EX;
2670 mp->offset = slotoffset;
2671
2672 /* __dict__ and __weakref__ are already filtered out */
2673 assert(strcmp(mp->name, "__dict__") != 0);
2674 assert(strcmp(mp->name, "__weakref__") != 0);
2675
2676 slotoffset += sizeof(PyObject *);
2677 }
2678 }
2679 if (add_dict) {
2680 if (base->tp_itemsize)
2681 type->tp_dictoffset = -(long)sizeof(PyObject *);
2682 else
2683 type->tp_dictoffset = slotoffset;
2684 slotoffset += sizeof(PyObject *);
2685 }
2686 if (add_weak) {
2687 assert(!base->tp_itemsize);
2688 type->tp_weaklistoffset = slotoffset;
2689 slotoffset += sizeof(PyObject *);
2690 }
2691 type->tp_basicsize = slotoffset;
2692 type->tp_itemsize = base->tp_itemsize;
2693 type->tp_members = PyHeapType_GET_MEMBERS(et);
2694
2695 if (type->tp_weaklistoffset && type->tp_dictoffset)
2696 type->tp_getset = subtype_getsets_full;
2697 else if (type->tp_weaklistoffset && !type->tp_dictoffset)
2698 type->tp_getset = subtype_getsets_weakref_only;
2699 else if (!type->tp_weaklistoffset && type->tp_dictoffset)
2700 type->tp_getset = subtype_getsets_dict_only;
2701 else
2702 type->tp_getset = NULL;
2703
2704 /* Special case some slots */
2705 if (type->tp_dictoffset != 0 || nslots > 0) {
2706 if (base->tp_getattr == NULL && base->tp_getattro == NULL)
2707 type->tp_getattro = PyObject_GenericGetAttr;
2708 if (base->tp_setattr == NULL && base->tp_setattro == NULL)
2709 type->tp_setattro = PyObject_GenericSetAttr;
2710 }
2711 type->tp_dealloc = subtype_dealloc;
2712
2713 /* Enable GC unless this class is not adding new instance variables and
2714 the base class did not use GC. */
2715 if ((base->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC) ||
2716 type->tp_basicsize > base->tp_basicsize)
2717 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC;
2718
2719 /* Always override allocation strategy to use regular heap */
2720 type->tp_alloc = PyType_GenericAlloc;
2721 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC) {
2722 type->tp_free = PyObject_GC_Del;
2723 type->tp_traverse = subtype_traverse;
2724 type->tp_clear = subtype_clear;
2725 }
2726 else
2727 type->tp_free = PyObject_Del;
2728
2729 /* store type in class' cell if one is supplied */
2730 cell = _PyDict_GetItemId(dict, &PyId___classcell__);
2731 if (cell != NULL) {
2732 /* At least one method requires a reference to its defining class */
2733 if (!PyCell_Check(cell)) {
2734 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2735 "__classcell__ must be a nonlocal cell, not %.200R",
2736 Py_TYPE(cell));
2737 goto error;
2738 }
2739 PyCell_Set(cell, (PyObject *) type);
2740 _PyDict_DelItemId(dict, &PyId___classcell__);
2741 PyErr_Clear();
2742 }
2743
2744 /* Initialize the rest */
2745 if (PyType_Ready(type) < 0)
2746 goto error;
2747
2748 /* Put the proper slots in place */
2749 fixup_slot_dispatchers(type);
2750
2751 if (type->tp_dictoffset) {
2752 et->ht_cached_keys = _PyDict_NewKeysForClass();
2753 }
2754
2755 if (set_names(type) < 0)
2756 goto error;
2757
2758 if (init_subclass(type, kwds) < 0)
2759 goto error;
2760
2761 Py_DECREF(dict);
2762 return (PyObject *)type;
2763
2764error:
2765 Py_XDECREF(dict);
2766 Py_XDECREF(bases);
2767 Py_XDECREF(slots);
2768 Py_XDECREF(type);
2769 return NULL;
2770}

2772static const short slotoffsets[] = {
2773 -1, /* invalid slot */
2774#include "typeslots.inc"
2775};
2776
2777PyObject *
2778PyType_FromSpecWithBases(PyType_Spec *spec, PyObject *bases)
2779{
2780 PyHeapTypeObject *res = (PyHeapTypeObject*)PyType_GenericAlloc(&PyType_Type, 0);
2781 PyTypeObject *type, *base;
2782 PyObject *modname;
2783 char *s;
2784 char *res_start = (char*)res;
2785 PyType_Slot *slot;
2786
2787 /* Set the type name and qualname */
2788 s = strrchr(spec->name, '.');
2789 if (s == NULL)
2790 s = (char*)spec->name;
2791 else
2792 s++;
2793
2794 if (res == NULL)
2795 return NULL;
2796 type = &res->ht_type;
2797 /* The flags must be initialized early, before the GC traverses us */
2798 type->tp_flags = spec->flags | Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE;
2799 res->ht_name = PyUnicode_FromString(s);
2800 if (!res->ht_name)
2801 goto fail;
2802 res->ht_qualname = res->ht_name;
2803 Py_INCREF(res->ht_qualname);
2804 type->tp_name = spec->name;
2805 if (!type->tp_name)
2806 goto fail;
2807
2808 /* Adjust for empty tuple bases */
2809 if (!bases) {
2810 base = &PyBaseObject_Type;
2811 /* See whether Py_tp_base(s) was specified */
2812 for (slot = spec->slots; slot->slot; slot++) {
2813 if (slot->slot == Py_tp_base)
2814 base = slot->pfunc;
2815 else if (slot->slot == Py_tp_bases) {
2816 bases = slot->pfunc;
2817 Py_INCREF(bases);
2818 }
2819 }
2820 if (!bases)
2821 bases = PyTuple_Pack(1, base);
2822 if (!bases)
2823 goto fail;
2824 }
2825 else
2826 Py_INCREF(bases);
2827
2828 /* Calculate best base, and check that all bases are type objects */
2829 base = best_base(bases);
2830 if (base == NULL) {
2831 goto fail;
2832 }
2833 if (!PyType_HasFeature(base, Py_TPFLAGS_BASETYPE)) {
2834 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2835 "type '%.100s' is not an acceptable base type",
2836 base->tp_name);
2837 goto fail;
2838 }
2839
2840 /* Initialize essential fields */
2841 type->tp_as_async = &res->as_async;
2842 type->tp_as_number = &res->as_number;
2843 type->tp_as_sequence = &res->as_sequence;
2844 type->tp_as_mapping = &res->as_mapping;
2845 type->tp_as_buffer = &res->as_buffer;
2846 /* Set tp_base and tp_bases */
2847 type->tp_bases = bases;
2848 bases = NULL;
2849 Py_INCREF(base);
2850 type->tp_base = base;
2851
2852 type->tp_basicsize = spec->basicsize;
2853 type->tp_itemsize = spec->itemsize;
2854
2855 for (slot = spec->slots; slot->slot; slot++) {
2856 if (slot->slot < 0
2857 || (size_t)slot->slot >= Py_ARRAY_LENGTH(slotoffsets)) {
2858 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, "invalid slot offset");
2859 goto fail;
2860 }
2861 if (slot->slot == Py_tp_base || slot->slot == Py_tp_bases)
2862 /* Processed above */
2863 continue;
2864 *(void**)(res_start + slotoffsets[slot->slot]) = slot->pfunc;
2865
2866 /* need to make a copy of the docstring slot, which usually
2867 points to a static string literal */
2868 if (slot->slot == Py_tp_doc) {
2869 const char *old_doc = _PyType_DocWithoutSignature(type->tp_name, slot->pfunc);
2870 size_t len = strlen(old_doc)+1;
2871 char *tp_doc = PyObject_MALLOC(len);
2872 if (tp_doc == NULL) {
2873 PyErr_NoMemory();
2874 goto fail;
2875 }
2876 memcpy(tp_doc, old_doc, len);
2877 type->tp_doc = tp_doc;
2878 }
2879 }
2880 if (type->tp_dealloc == NULL) {
2881 /* It's a heap type, so needs the heap types' dealloc.
2882 subtype_dealloc will call the base type's tp_dealloc, if
2883 necessary. */
2884 type->tp_dealloc = subtype_dealloc;
2885 }
2886
2887 if (PyType_Ready(type) < 0)
2888 goto fail;
2889
2890 if (type->tp_dictoffset) {
2891 res->ht_cached_keys = _PyDict_NewKeysForClass();
2892 }
2893
2894 /* Set type.__module__ */
2895 s = strrchr(spec->name, '.');
2896 if (s != NULL) {
2897 int err;
2898 modname = PyUnicode_FromStringAndSize(
2899 spec->name, (Py_ssize_t)(s - spec->name));
2900 if (modname == NULL) {
2901 goto fail;
2902 }
2903 err = _PyDict_SetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___module__, modname);
2904 Py_DECREF(modname);
2905 if (err != 0)
2906 goto fail;
2907 } else {
2908 if (PyErr_WarnFormat(PyExc_DeprecationWarning, 1,
2909 "builtin type %.200s has no __module__ attribute",
2910 spec->name))
2911 goto fail;
2912 }
2913
2914 return (PyObject*)res;
2915
2916 fail:
2917 Py_DECREF(res);
2918 return NULL;
2919}

2927void *
2928PyType_GetSlot(PyTypeObject *type, int slot)
2929{
2930 if (!PyType_HasFeature(type, Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE) || slot < 0) {
2931 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
2932 return NULL;
2933 }
2934 if ((size_t)slot >= Py_ARRAY_LENGTH(slotoffsets)) {
2935 /* Extension module requesting slot from a future version */
2936 return NULL;
2937 }
2938 return *(void**)(((char*)type) + slotoffsets[slot]);

2941/* Internal API to look for a name through the MRO.
2942 This returns a borrowed reference, and doesn't set an exception! */
2943PyObject *
2944_PyType_Lookup(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *name)
2945{
2946 Py_ssize_t i, n;
2947 PyObject *mro, *res, *base, *dict;
2948 unsigned int h;
2949
2950 if (MCACHE_CACHEABLE_NAME(name) &&
2951 PyType_HasFeature(type, Py_TPFLAGS_VALID_VERSION_TAG)) {
2952 /* fast path */
2953 h = MCACHE_HASH_METHOD(type, name);
2954 if (method_cache[h].version == type->tp_version_tag &&
2955 method_cache[h].name == name) {
2956#if MCACHE_STATS
2957 method_cache_hits++;
2958#endif
2959 return method_cache[h].value;
2960 }
2961 }
2962
2963 /* Look in tp_dict of types in MRO */
2964 mro = type->tp_mro;
2965
2966 if (mro == NULL) {
2967 if ((type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_READYING) == 0 &&
2968 PyType_Ready(type) < 0) {
2969 /* It's not ideal to clear the error condition,
2970 but this function is documented as not setting
2971 an exception, and I don't want to change that.
2972 When PyType_Ready() can't proceed, it won't
2973 set the "ready" flag, so future attempts to ready
2974 the same type will call it again -- hopefully
2975 in a context that propagates the exception out.
2976 */
2977 PyErr_Clear();
2978 return NULL;
2979 }
2980 mro = type->tp_mro;
2981 if (mro == NULL) {
2982 return NULL;
2983 }
2984 }
2985
2986 res = NULL;
2987 /* keep a strong reference to mro because type->tp_mro can be replaced
2988 during PyDict_GetItem(dict, name) */
2989 Py_INCREF(mro);
2990 assert(PyTuple_Check(mro));
2991 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(mro);
2992 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
2993 base = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(mro, i);
2994 assert(PyType_Check(base));
2995 dict = ((PyTypeObject *)base)->tp_dict;
2996 assert(dict && PyDict_Check(dict));
2997 res = PyDict_GetItem(dict, name);
2998 if (res != NULL)
2999 break;
3000 }
3001 Py_DECREF(mro);
3002
3003 if (MCACHE_CACHEABLE_NAME(name) && assign_version_tag(type)) {
3004 h = MCACHE_HASH_METHOD(type, name);
3005 method_cache[h].version = type->tp_version_tag;
3006 method_cache[h].value = res; /* borrowed */
3007 Py_INCREF(name);
3008 assert(((PyASCIIObject *)(name))->hash != -1);
3009#if MCACHE_STATS
3010 if (method_cache[h].name != Py_None && method_cache[h].name != name)
3011 method_cache_collisions++;
3012 else
3013 method_cache_misses++;
3014#endif
3015 Py_SETREF(method_cache[h].name, name);
3016 }
3017 return res;
3018}

3020PyObject *
3021_PyType_LookupId(PyTypeObject *type, struct _Py_Identifier *name)
3022{
3023 PyObject *oname;
3024 oname = _PyUnicode_FromId(name); /* borrowed */
3025 if (oname == NULL)
3026 return NULL;
3027 return _PyType_Lookup(type, oname);
3028}

3030/* This is similar to PyObject_GenericGetAttr(),
3031 but uses _PyType_Lookup() instead of just looking in type->tp_dict. */
3032static PyObject *
3033type_getattro(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *name)
3034{
3035 PyTypeObject *metatype = Py_TYPE(type);
3036 PyObject *meta_attribute, *attribute;
3037 descrgetfunc meta_get;
3038
3039 if (!PyUnicode_Check(name)) {
3040 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3041 "attribute name must be string, not '%.200s'",
3042 name->ob_type->tp_name);
3043 return NULL;
3044 }
3045
3046 /* Initialize this type (we'll assume the metatype is initialized) */
3047 if (type->tp_dict == NULL) {
3048 if (PyType_Ready(type) < 0)
3049 return NULL;
3050 }
3051
3052 /* No readable descriptor found yet */
3053 meta_get = NULL;
3054
3055 /* Look for the attribute in the metatype */
3056 meta_attribute = _PyType_Lookup(metatype, name);
3057
3058 if (meta_attribute != NULL) {
3059 meta_get = Py_TYPE(meta_attribute)->tp_descr_get;
3060
3061 if (meta_get != NULL && PyDescr_IsData(meta_attribute)) {
3062 /* Data descriptors implement tp_descr_set to intercept
3063 * writes. Assume the attribute is not overridden in
3064 * type's tp_dict (and bases): call the descriptor now.
3065 */
3066 return meta_get(meta_attribute, (PyObject *)type,
3067 (PyObject *)metatype);
3068 }
3069 Py_INCREF(meta_attribute);
3070 }
3071
3072 /* No data descriptor found on metatype. Look in tp_dict of this
3073 * type and its bases */
3074 attribute = _PyType_Lookup(type, name);
3075 if (attribute != NULL) {
3076 /* Implement descriptor functionality, if any */
3077 descrgetfunc local_get = Py_TYPE(attribute)->tp_descr_get;
3078
3079 Py_XDECREF(meta_attribute);
3080
3081 if (local_get != NULL) {
3082 /* NULL 2nd argument indicates the descriptor was
3083 * found on the target object itself (or a base) */
3084 return local_get(attribute, (PyObject *)NULL,
3085 (PyObject *)type);
3086 }
3087
3088 Py_INCREF(attribute);
3089 return attribute;
3090 }
3091
3092 /* No attribute found in local __dict__ (or bases): use the
3093 * descriptor from the metatype, if any */
3094 if (meta_get != NULL) {
3095 PyObject *res;
3096 res = meta_get(meta_attribute, (PyObject *)type,
3097 (PyObject *)metatype);
3098 Py_DECREF(meta_attribute);
3099 return res;
3100 }
3101
3102 /* If an ordinary attribute was found on the metatype, return it now */
3103 if (meta_attribute != NULL) {
3104 return meta_attribute;
3105 }
3106
3107 /* Give up */
3108 PyErr_Format(PyExc_AttributeError,
3109 "type object '%.50s' has no attribute '%U'",
3110 type->tp_name, name);
3111 return NULL;
3112}
