3114static int
3115type_setattro(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *name, PyObject *value)
3116{
3117 int res;
3118 if (!(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)) {
3119 PyErr_Format(
3120 PyExc_TypeError,
3121 "can't set attributes of built-in/extension type '%s'",
3122 type->tp_name);
3123 return -1;
3124 }
3125 if (PyUnicode_Check(name)) {
3126 if (PyUnicode_CheckExact(name)) {
3127 if (PyUnicode_READY(name) == -1)
3128 return -1;
3129 Py_INCREF(name);
3130 }
3131 else {
3132 name = _PyUnicode_Copy(name);
3133 if (name == NULL)
3134 return -1;
3135 }
3136 PyUnicode_InternInPlace(&name);
3137 if (!PyUnicode_CHECK_INTERNED(name)) {
3138 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_MemoryError,
3139 "Out of memory interning an attribute name");
3140 Py_DECREF(name);
3141 return -1;
3142 }
3143 }
3144 else {
3145 /* Will fail in _PyObject_GenericSetAttrWithDict. */
3146 Py_INCREF(name);
3147 }
3148 res = _PyObject_GenericSetAttrWithDict((PyObject *)type, name, value, NULL);
3149 if (res == 0) {
3150 res = update_slot(type, name);
3151 assert(_PyType_CheckConsistency(type));
3152 }
3153 Py_DECREF(name);
3154 return res;
3155}

3160static void
3161type_dealloc(PyTypeObject *type)
3162{
3163 PyHeapTypeObject *et;
3164 PyObject *tp, *val, *tb;
3165
3166 /* Assert this is a heap-allocated type object */
3167 assert(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE);
3168 _PyObject_GC_UNTRACK(type);
3169 PyErr_Fetch(&tp, &val, &tb);
3170 remove_all_subclasses(type, type->tp_bases);
3171 PyErr_Restore(tp, val, tb);
3172 PyObject_ClearWeakRefs((PyObject *)type);
3173 et = (PyHeapTypeObject *)type;
3174 Py_XDECREF(type->tp_base);
3175 Py_XDECREF(type->tp_dict);
3176 Py_XDECREF(type->tp_bases);
3177 Py_XDECREF(type->tp_mro);
3178 Py_XDECREF(type->tp_cache);
3179 Py_XDECREF(type->tp_subclasses);
3180 /* A type's tp_doc is heap allocated, unlike the tp_doc slots
3181 * of most other objects. It's okay to cast it to char *.
3182 */
3183 PyObject_Free((char *)type->tp_doc);
3184 Py_XDECREF(et->ht_name);
3185 Py_XDECREF(et->ht_qualname);
3186 Py_XDECREF(et->ht_slots);
3187 if (et->ht_cached_keys)
3188 _PyDictKeys_DecRef(et->ht_cached_keys);
3189 Py_TYPE(type)->tp_free((PyObject *)type);
3190}

3233/*
3234 Merge the __dict__ of aclass into dict, and recursively also all
3235 the __dict__s of aclass's base classes. The order of merging isn't
3236 defined, as it's expected that only the final set of dict keys is
3237 interesting.
3238 Return 0 on success, -1 on error.
3239*/
3240
3241static int
3242merge_class_dict(PyObject *dict, PyObject *aclass)
3243{
3244 PyObject *classdict;
3245 PyObject *bases;
3246 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__bases__);
3247
3248 assert(PyDict_Check(dict));
3249 assert(aclass);
3250
3251 /* Merge in the type's dict (if any). */
3252 classdict = _PyObject_GetAttrId(aclass, &PyId___dict__);
3253 if (classdict == NULL)
3254 PyErr_Clear();
3255 else {
3256 int status = PyDict_Update(dict, classdict);
3257 Py_DECREF(classdict);
3258 if (status < 0)
3259 return -1;
3260 }
3261
3262 /* Recursively merge in the base types' (if any) dicts. */
3263 bases = _PyObject_GetAttrId(aclass, &PyId___bases__);
3264 if (bases == NULL)
3265 PyErr_Clear();
3266 else {
3267 /* We have no guarantee that bases is a real tuple */
3268 Py_ssize_t i, n;
3269 n = PySequence_Size(bases); /* This better be right */
3270 if (n < 0)
3271 PyErr_Clear();
3272 else {
3273 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
3274 int status;
3275 PyObject *base = PySequence_GetItem(bases, i);
3276 if (base == NULL) {
3277 Py_DECREF(bases);
3278 return -1;
3279 }
3280 status = merge_class_dict(dict, base);
3281 Py_DECREF(base);
3282 if (status < 0) {
3283 Py_DECREF(bases);
3284 return -1;
3285 }
3286 }
3287 }
3288 Py_DECREF(bases);
3289 }
3290 return 0;
3291}

3359static int
3360type_traverse(PyTypeObject *type, visitproc visit, void *arg)
3361{
3362 /* Because of type_is_gc(), the collector only calls this
3363 for heaptypes. */
3364 if (!(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)) {
3365 char msg[200];
3366 sprintf(msg, "type_traverse() called for non-heap type '%.100s'",
3367 type->tp_name);
3368 Py_FatalError(msg);
3369 }
3370
3371 Py_VISIT(type->tp_dict);
3372 Py_VISIT(type->tp_cache);
3373 Py_VISIT(type->tp_mro);
3374 Py_VISIT(type->tp_bases);
3375 Py_VISIT(type->tp_base);
3376
3377 /* There's no need to visit type->tp_subclasses or
3378 ((PyHeapTypeObject *)type)->ht_slots, because they can't be involved
3379 in cycles; tp_subclasses is a list of weak references,
3380 and slots is a tuple of strings. */
3381
3382 return 0;
3383}
3384
3385static int
3386type_clear(PyTypeObject *type)
3387{
3388 PyDictKeysObject *cached_keys;
3389 /* Because of type_is_gc(), the collector only calls this
3390 for heaptypes. */
3391 assert(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE);
3392
3393 /* We need to invalidate the method cache carefully before clearing
3394 the dict, so that other objects caught in a reference cycle
3395 don't start calling destroyed methods.
3396
3397 Otherwise, the only field we need to clear is tp_mro, which is
3398 part of a hard cycle (its first element is the class itself) that
3399 won't be broken otherwise (it's a tuple and tuples don't have a
3400 tp_clear handler). None of the other fields need to be
3401 cleared, and here's why:
3402
3403 tp_cache:
3404 Not used; if it were, it would be a dict.
3405
3406 tp_bases, tp_base:
3407 If these are involved in a cycle, there must be at least
3408 one other, mutable object in the cycle, e.g. a base
3409 class's dict; the cycle will be broken that way.
3410
3411 tp_subclasses:
3412 A dict of weak references can't be part of a cycle; and
3413 dicts have their own tp_clear.
3414
3415 slots (in PyHeapTypeObject):
3416 A tuple of strings can't be part of a cycle.
3417 */
3418
3419 PyType_Modified(type);
3420 cached_keys = ((PyHeapTypeObject *)type)->ht_cached_keys;
3421 if (cached_keys != NULL) {
3422 ((PyHeapTypeObject *)type)->ht_cached_keys = NULL;
3423 _PyDictKeys_DecRef(cached_keys);
3424 }
3425 if (type->tp_dict)
3426 PyDict_Clear(type->tp_dict);
3427 Py_CLEAR(type->tp_mro);
3428
3429 return 0;
3430}

3432static int
3433type_is_gc(PyTypeObject *type)
3434{
3435 return type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE;
3436}

3483/* The base type of all types (eventually)... except itself. */
3484
3485/* You may wonder why object.__new__() only complains about arguments
3486 when object.__init__() is not overridden, and vice versa.
3487
3488 Consider the use cases:
3489
3490 1. When neither is overridden, we want to hear complaints about
3491 excess (i.e., any) arguments, since their presence could
3492 indicate there's a bug.
3493
3494 2. When defining an Immutable type, we are likely to override only
3495 __new__(), since __init__() is called too late to initialize an
3496 Immutable object. Since __new__() defines the signature for the
3497 type, it would be a pain to have to override __init__() just to
3498 stop it from complaining about excess arguments.
3499
3500 3. When defining a Mutable type, we are likely to override only
3501 __init__(). So here the converse reasoning applies: we don't
3502 want to have to override __new__() just to stop it from
3503 complaining.
3504
3505 4. When __init__() is overridden, and the subclass __init__() calls
3506 object.__init__(), the latter should complain about excess
3507 arguments; ditto for __new__().
3508
3509 Use cases 2 and 3 make it unattractive to unconditionally check for
3510 excess arguments. The best solution that addresses all four use
3511 cases is as follows: __init__() complains about excess arguments
3512 unless __new__() is overridden and __init__() is not overridden
3513 (IOW, if __init__() is overridden or __new__() is not overridden);
3514 symmetrically, __new__() complains about excess arguments unless
3515 __init__() is overridden and __new__() is not overridden
3516 (IOW, if __new__() is overridden or __init__() is not overridden).
3517
3518 However, for backwards compatibility, this breaks too much code.
3519 Therefore, in 2.6, we'll *warn* about excess arguments when both
3520 methods are overridden; for all other cases we'll use the above
3521 rules.
3522
3523*/
3524
3525/* Forward */
3526static PyObject *
3527object_new(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds);
3528
3529static int
3530excess_args(PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
3531{
3532 return PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args) ||
3533 (kwds && PyDict_Check(kwds) && PyDict_GET_SIZE(kwds));
3534}
3535
3536static int
3537object_init(PyObject *self, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
3538{
3539 int err = 0;
3540 PyTypeObject *type = Py_TYPE(self);
3541 if (excess_args(args, kwds) &&
3542 (type->tp_new == object_new || type->tp_init != object_init)) {
3543 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError, "object.__init__() takes no parameters");
3544 err = -1;
3545 }
3546 return err;
3547}
3548
3549static PyObject *
3550object_new(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
3551{
3552 if (excess_args(args, kwds) &&
3553 (type->tp_init == object_init || type->tp_new != object_new)) {
3554 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError, "object() takes no parameters");
3555 return NULL;
3556 }
3557
3558 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_IS_ABSTRACT) {
3559 PyObject *abstract_methods = NULL;
3560 PyObject *builtins;
3561 PyObject *sorted;
3562 PyObject *sorted_methods = NULL;
3563 PyObject *joined = NULL;
3564 PyObject *comma;
3565 _Py_static_string(comma_id, ", ");
3566 _Py_IDENTIFIER(sorted);
3567
3568 /* Compute ", ".join(sorted(type.__abstractmethods__))
3569 into joined. */
3570 abstract_methods = type_abstractmethods(type, NULL);
3571 if (abstract_methods == NULL)
3572 goto error;
3573 builtins = PyEval_GetBuiltins();
3574 if (builtins == NULL)
3575 goto error;
3576 sorted = _PyDict_GetItemId(builtins, &PyId_sorted);
3577 if (sorted == NULL)
3578 goto error;
3579 sorted_methods = PyObject_CallFunctionObjArgs(sorted,
3580 abstract_methods,
3581 NULL);
3582 if (sorted_methods == NULL)
3583 goto error;
3584 comma = _PyUnicode_FromId(&comma_id);
3585 if (comma == NULL)
3586 goto error;
3587 joined = PyUnicode_Join(comma, sorted_methods);
3588 if (joined == NULL)
3589 goto error;
3590
3591 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3592 "Can't instantiate abstract class %s "
3593 "with abstract methods %U",
3594 type->tp_name,
3595 joined);
3596 error:
3597 Py_XDECREF(joined);
3598 Py_XDECREF(sorted_methods);
3599 Py_XDECREF(abstract_methods);
3600 return NULL;
3601 }
3602 return type->tp_alloc(type, 0);
3603}

3611static PyObject *
3612object_repr(PyObject *self)
3613{
3614 PyTypeObject *type;
3615 PyObject *mod, *name, *rtn;
3616
3617 type = Py_TYPE(self);
3618 mod = type_module(type, NULL);
3619 if (mod == NULL)
3620 PyErr_Clear();
3621 else if (!PyUnicode_Check(mod)) {
3622 Py_DECREF(mod);
3623 mod = NULL;
3624 }
3625 name = type_qualname(type, NULL);
3626 if (name == NULL) {
3627 Py_XDECREF(mod);
3628 return NULL;
3629 }
3630 if (mod != NULL && !_PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(mod, &PyId_builtins))
3631 rtn = PyUnicode_FromFormat("<%U.%U object at %p>", mod, name, self);
3632 else
3633 rtn = PyUnicode_FromFormat("<%s object at %p>",
3634 type->tp_name, self);
3635 Py_XDECREF(mod);
3636 Py_DECREF(name);
3637 return rtn;
3638}

3650
3651static PyObject *
3652object_richcompare(PyObject *self, PyObject *other, int op)
3653{
3654 PyObject *res;
3655
3656 switch (op) {
3657
3658 case Py_EQ:
3659 /* Return NotImplemented instead of False, so if two
3660 objects are compared, both get a chance at the
3661 comparison. See issue #1393. */
3662 res = (self == other) ? Py_True : Py_NotImplemented;
3663 Py_INCREF(res);
3664 break;
3665
3666 case Py_NE:
3667 /* By default, __ne__() delegates to __eq__() and inverts the result,
3668 unless the latter returns NotImplemented. */
3669 if (self->ob_type->tp_richcompare == NULL) {
3670 res = Py_NotImplemented;
3671 Py_INCREF(res);
3672 break;
3673 }
3674 res = (*self->ob_type->tp_richcompare)(self, other, Py_EQ);
3675 if (res != NULL && res != Py_NotImplemented) {
3676 int ok = PyObject_IsTrue(res);
3677 Py_DECREF(res);
3678 if (ok < 0)
3679 res = NULL;
3680 else {
3681 if (ok)
3682 res = Py_False;
3683 else
3684 res = Py_True;
3685 Py_INCREF(res);
3686 }
3687 }
3688 break;
3689
3690 default:
3691 res = Py_NotImplemented;
3692 Py_INCREF(res);
3693 break;
3694 }
3695
3696 return res;
3697}

3706static int
3707compatible_with_tp_base(PyTypeObject *child)
3708{
3709 PyTypeObject *parent = child->tp_base;
3710 return (parent != NULL &&
3711 child->tp_basicsize == parent->tp_basicsize &&
3712 child->tp_itemsize == parent->tp_itemsize &&
3713 child->tp_dictoffset == parent->tp_dictoffset &&
3714 child->tp_weaklistoffset == parent->tp_weaklistoffset &&
3715 ((child->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC) ==
3716 (parent->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC)) &&
3717 (child->tp_dealloc == subtype_dealloc ||
3718 child->tp_dealloc == parent->tp_dealloc));
3719}
3720
3721static int
3722same_slots_added(PyTypeObject *a, PyTypeObject *b)
3723{
3724 PyTypeObject *base = a->tp_base;
3725 Py_ssize_t size;
3726 PyObject *slots_a, *slots_b;
3727
3728 assert(base == b->tp_base);
3729 size = base->tp_basicsize;
3730 if (a->tp_dictoffset == size && b->tp_dictoffset == size)
3731 size += sizeof(PyObject *);
3732 if (a->tp_weaklistoffset == size && b->tp_weaklistoffset == size)
3733 size += sizeof(PyObject *);
3734
3735 /* Check slots compliance */
3736 if (!(a->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE) ||
3737 !(b->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)) {
3738 return 0;
3739 }
3740 slots_a = ((PyHeapTypeObject *)a)->ht_slots;
3741 slots_b = ((PyHeapTypeObject *)b)->ht_slots;
3742 if (slots_a && slots_b) {
3743 if (PyObject_RichCompareBool(slots_a, slots_b, Py_EQ) != 1)
3744 return 0;
3745 size += sizeof(PyObject *) * PyTuple_GET_SIZE(slots_a);
3746 }
3747 return size == a->tp_basicsize && size == b->tp_basicsize;
3748}
3749
3750static int
3751compatible_for_assignment(PyTypeObject* oldto, PyTypeObject* newto, const char* attr)
3752{
3753 PyTypeObject *newbase, *oldbase;
3754
3755 if (newto->tp_free != oldto->tp_free) {
3756 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3757 "%s assignment: "
3758 "'%s' deallocator differs from '%s'",
3759 attr,
3760 newto->tp_name,
3761 oldto->tp_name);
3762 return 0;
3763 }
3764 /*
3765 It's tricky to tell if two arbitrary types are sufficiently compatible as
3766 to be interchangeable; e.g., even if they have the same tp_basicsize, they
3767 might have totally different struct fields. It's much easier to tell if a
3768 type and its supertype are compatible; e.g., if they have the same
3769 tp_basicsize, then that means they have identical fields. So to check
3770 whether two arbitrary types are compatible, we first find the highest
3771 supertype that each is compatible with, and then if those supertypes are
3772 compatible then the original types must also be compatible.
3773 */
3774 newbase = newto;
3775 oldbase = oldto;
3776 while (compatible_with_tp_base(newbase))
3777 newbase = newbase->tp_base;
3778 while (compatible_with_tp_base(oldbase))
3779 oldbase = oldbase->tp_base;
3780 if (newbase != oldbase &&
3781 (newbase->tp_base != oldbase->tp_base ||
3782 !same_slots_added(newbase, oldbase))) {
3783 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3784 "%s assignment: "
3785 "'%s' object layout differs from '%s'",
3786 attr,
3787 newto->tp_name,
3788 oldto->tp_name);
3789 return 0;
3790 }
3791
3792 return 1;
3793}
3794
3795static int
3796object_set_class(PyObject *self, PyObject *value, void *closure)
3797{
3798 PyTypeObject *oldto = Py_TYPE(self);
3799 PyTypeObject *newto;
3800
3801 if (value == NULL) {
3802 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
3803 "can't delete __class__ attribute");
3804 return -1;
3805 }
3806 if (!PyType_Check(value)) {
3807 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3808 "__class__ must be set to a class, not '%s' object",
3809 Py_TYPE(value)->tp_name);
3810 return -1;
3811 }
3812 newto = (PyTypeObject *)value;
3813 /* In versions of CPython prior to 3.5, the code in
3814 compatible_for_assignment was not set up to correctly check for memory
3815 layout / slot / etc. compatibility for non-HEAPTYPE classes, so we just
3816 disallowed __class__ assignment in any case that wasn't HEAPTYPE ->
3817 HEAPTYPE.
3818
3819 During the 3.5 development cycle, we fixed the code in
3820 compatible_for_assignment to correctly check compatibility between
3821 arbitrary types, and started allowing __class__ assignment in all cases
3822 where the old and new types did in fact have compatible slots and
3823 memory layout (regardless of whether they were implemented as HEAPTYPEs
3824 or not).
3825
3826 Just before 3.5 was released, though, we discovered that this led to
3827 problems with immutable types like int, where the interpreter assumes
3828 they are immutable and interns some values. Formerly this wasn't a
3829 problem, because they really were immutable -- in particular, all the
3830 types where the interpreter applied this interning trick happened to
3831 also be statically allocated, so the old HEAPTYPE rules were
3832 "accidentally" stopping them from allowing __class__ assignment. But
3833 with the changes to __class__ assignment, we started allowing code like
3834
3835 class MyInt(int):
3836 ...
3837 # Modifies the type of *all* instances of 1 in the whole program,
3838 # including future instances (!), because the 1 object is interned.
3839 (1).__class__ = MyInt
3840
3841 (see https://bugs.python.org/issue24912).
3842
3843 In theory the proper fix would be to identify which classes rely on
3844 this invariant and somehow disallow __class__ assignment only for them,
3845 perhaps via some mechanism like a new Py_TPFLAGS_IMMUTABLE flag (a
3846 "blacklisting" approach). But in practice, since this problem wasn't
3847 noticed late in the 3.5 RC cycle, we're taking the conservative
3848 approach and reinstating the same HEAPTYPE->HEAPTYPE check that we used
3849 to have, plus a "whitelist". For now, the whitelist consists only of
3850 ModuleType subtypes, since those are the cases that motivated the patch
3851 in the first place -- see https://bugs.python.org/issue22986 -- and
3852 since module objects are mutable we can be sure that they are
3853 definitely not being interned. So now we allow HEAPTYPE->HEAPTYPE *or*
3854 ModuleType subtype -> ModuleType subtype.
3855
3856 So far as we know, all the code beyond the following 'if' statement
3857 will correctly handle non-HEAPTYPE classes, and the HEAPTYPE check is
3858 needed only to protect that subset of non-HEAPTYPE classes for which
3859 the interpreter has baked in the assumption that all instances are
3860 truly immutable.
3861 */
3862 if (!(PyType_IsSubtype(newto, &PyModule_Type) &&
3863 PyType_IsSubtype(oldto, &PyModule_Type)) &&
3864 (!(newto->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE) ||
3865 !(oldto->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE))) {
3866 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3867 "__class__ assignment only supported for heap types "
3868 "or ModuleType subclasses");
3869 return -1;
3870 }
3871
3872 if (compatible_for_assignment(oldto, newto, "__class__")) {
3873 if (newto->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
3874 Py_INCREF(newto);
3875 Py_TYPE(self) = newto;
3876 if (oldto->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
3877 Py_DECREF(oldto);
3878 return 0;
3879 }
3880 else {
3881 return -1;
3882 }
3883}

3892/* Stuff to implement __reduce_ex__ for pickle protocols >= 2.
3893 We fall back to helpers in copyreg for:
3894 - pickle protocols < 2
3895 - calculating the list of slot names (done only once per class)
3896 - the __newobj__ function (which is used as a token but never called)
3897*/
3898
3899static PyObject *
3900import_copyreg(void)
3901{
3902 PyObject *copyreg_str;
3903 PyObject *copyreg_module;
3904 PyInterpreterState *interp = PyThreadState_GET()->interp;
3905 _Py_IDENTIFIER(copyreg);
3906
3907 copyreg_str = _PyUnicode_FromId(&PyId_copyreg);
3908 if (copyreg_str == NULL) {
3909 return NULL;
3910 }
3911 /* Try to fetch cached copy of copyreg from sys.modules first in an
3912 attempt to avoid the import overhead. Previously this was implemented
3913 by storing a reference to the cached module in a static variable, but
3914 this broke when multiple embedded interpreters were in use (see issue
3915 #17408 and #19088). */
3916 copyreg_module = PyDict_GetItemWithError(interp->modules, copyreg_str);
3917 if (copyreg_module != NULL) {
3918 Py_INCREF(copyreg_module);
3919 return copyreg_module;
3920 }
3921 if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
3922 return NULL;
3923 }
3924 return PyImport_Import(copyreg_str);
3925}

3927static PyObject *
3928_PyType_GetSlotNames(PyTypeObject *cls)
3929{
3930 PyObject *copyreg;
3931 PyObject *slotnames;
3932 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__slotnames__);
3933 _Py_IDENTIFIER(_slotnames);
3934
3935 assert(PyType_Check(cls));
3936
3937 /* Get the slot names from the cache in the class if possible. */
3938 slotnames = _PyDict_GetItemIdWithError(cls->tp_dict, &PyId___slotnames__);
3939 if (slotnames != NULL) {
3940 if (slotnames != Py_None && !PyList_Check(slotnames)) {
3941 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3942 "%.200s.__slotnames__ should be a list or None, "
3943 "not %.200s",
3944 cls->tp_name, Py_TYPE(slotnames)->tp_name);
3945 return NULL;
3946 }
3947 Py_INCREF(slotnames);
3948 return slotnames;
3949 }
3950 else {
3951 if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
3952 return NULL;
3953 }
3954 /* The class does not have the slot names cached yet. */
3955 }
3956
3957 copyreg = import_copyreg();
3958 if (copyreg == NULL)
3959 return NULL;
3960
3961 /* Use _slotnames function from the copyreg module to find the slots
3962 by this class and its bases. This function will cache the result
3963 in __slotnames__. */
3964 slotnames = _PyObject_CallMethodIdObjArgs(copyreg, &PyId__slotnames,
3965 cls, NULL);
3966 Py_DECREF(copyreg);
3967 if (slotnames == NULL)
3968 return NULL;
3969
3970 if (slotnames != Py_None && !PyList_Check(slotnames)) {
3971 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
3972 "copyreg._slotnames didn't return a list or None");
3973 Py_DECREF(slotnames);
3974 return NULL;
3975 }
3976
3977 return slotnames;
3978}

3980static PyObject *
3981_PyObject_GetState(PyObject *obj, int required)
3982{
3983 PyObject *state;
3984 PyObject *getstate;
3985 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__getstate__);
3986
3987 getstate = _PyObject_GetAttrId(obj, &PyId___getstate__);
3988 if (getstate == NULL) {
3989 PyObject *slotnames;
3990
3991 if (!PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_AttributeError)) {
3992 return NULL;
3993 }
3994 PyErr_Clear();
3995
3996 if (required && obj->ob_type->tp_itemsize) {
3997 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3998 "can't pickle %.200s objects",
3999 Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_name);
4000 return NULL;
4001 }
4002
4003 {
4004 PyObject **dict;
4005 dict = _PyObject_GetDictPtr(obj);
4006 /* It is possible that the object's dict is not initialized
4007 yet. In this case, we will return None for the state.
4008 We also return None if the dict is empty to make the behavior
4009 consistent regardless whether the dict was initialized or not.
4010 This make unit testing easier. */
4011 if (dict != NULL && *dict != NULL && PyDict_GET_SIZE(*dict)) {
4012 state = *dict;
4013 }
4014 else {
4015 state = Py_None;
4016 }
4017 Py_INCREF(state);
4018 }
4019
4020 slotnames = _PyType_GetSlotNames(Py_TYPE(obj));
4021 if (slotnames == NULL) {
4022 Py_DECREF(state);
4023 return NULL;
4024 }
4025
4026 assert(slotnames == Py_None || PyList_Check(slotnames));
4027 if (required) {
4028 Py_ssize_t basicsize = PyBaseObject_Type.tp_basicsize;
4029 if (obj->ob_type->tp_dictoffset)
4030 basicsize += sizeof(PyObject *);
4031 if (obj->ob_type->tp_weaklistoffset)
4032 basicsize += sizeof(PyObject *);
4033 if (slotnames != Py_None)
4034 basicsize += sizeof(PyObject *) * PyList_GET_SIZE(slotnames);
4035 if (obj->ob_type->tp_basicsize > basicsize) {
4036 Py_DECREF(slotnames);
4037 Py_DECREF(state);
4038 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
4039 "can't pickle %.200s objects",
4040 Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_name);
4041 return NULL;
4042 }
4043 }
4044
4045 if (slotnames != Py_None && PyList_GET_SIZE(slotnames) > 0) {
4046 PyObject *slots;
4047 Py_ssize_t slotnames_size, i;
4048
4049 slots = PyDict_New();
4050 if (slots == NULL) {
4051 Py_DECREF(slotnames);
4052 Py_DECREF(state);
4053 return NULL;
4054 }
4055
4056 slotnames_size = PyList_GET_SIZE(slotnames);
4057 for (i = 0; i < slotnames_size; i++) {
4058 PyObject *name, *value;
4059
4060 name = PyList_GET_ITEM(slotnames, i);
4061 Py_INCREF(name);
4062 value = PyObject_GetAttr(obj, name);
4063 if (value == NULL) {
4064 Py_DECREF(name);
4065 if (!PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_AttributeError)) {
4066 goto error;
4067 }
4068 /* It is not an error if the attribute is not present. */
4069 PyErr_Clear();
4070 }
4071 else {
4072 int err = PyDict_SetItem(slots, name, value);
4073 Py_DECREF(name);
4074 Py_DECREF(value);
4075 if (err) {
4076 goto error;
4077 }
4078 }
4079
4080 /* The list is stored on the class so it may mutate while we
4081 iterate over it */
4082 if (slotnames_size != PyList_GET_SIZE(slotnames)) {
4083 PyErr_Format(PyExc_RuntimeError,
4084 "__slotsname__ changed size during iteration");
4085 goto error;
4086 }
4087
4088 /* We handle errors within the loop here. */
4089 if (0) {
4090 error:
4091 Py_DECREF(slotnames);
4092 Py_DECREF(slots);
4093 Py_DECREF(state);
4094 return NULL;
4095 }
4096 }
4097
4098 /* If we found some slot attributes, pack them in a tuple along
4099 the original attribute dictionary. */
4100 if (PyDict_GET_SIZE(slots) > 0) {
4101 PyObject *state2;
4102
4103 state2 = PyTuple_Pack(2, state, slots);
4104 Py_DECREF(state);
4105 if (state2 == NULL) {
4106 Py_DECREF(slotnames);
4107 Py_DECREF(slots);
4108 return NULL;
4109 }
4110 state = state2;
4111 }
4112 Py_DECREF(slots);
4113 }
4114 Py_DECREF(slotnames);
4115 }
4116 else { /* getstate != NULL */
4117 state = _PyObject_CallNoArg(getstate);
4118 Py_DECREF(getstate);
4119 if (state == NULL)
4120 return NULL;
4121 }
4122
4123 return state;
4124}
4125
4126static int
4127_PyObject_GetNewArguments(PyObject *obj, PyObject **args, PyObject **kwargs)
4128{
4129 PyObject *getnewargs, *getnewargs_ex;
4130 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__getnewargs_ex__);
4131 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__getnewargs__);
4132
4133 if (args == NULL || kwargs == NULL) {
4134 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
4135 return -1;
4136 }
4137
4138 /* We first attempt to fetch the arguments for __new__ by calling
4139 __getnewargs_ex__ on the object. */
4140 getnewargs_ex = _PyObject_LookupSpecial(obj, &PyId___getnewargs_ex__);
4141 if (getnewargs_ex != NULL) {
4142 PyObject *newargs = _PyObject_CallNoArg(getnewargs_ex);
4143 Py_DECREF(getnewargs_ex);
4144 if (newargs == NULL) {
4145 return -1;
4146 }
4147 if (!PyTuple_Check(newargs)) {
4148 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
4149 "__getnewargs_ex__ should return a tuple, "
4150 "not '%.200s'", Py_TYPE(newargs)->tp_name);
4151 Py_DECREF(newargs);
4152 return -1;
4153 }
4154 if (PyTuple_GET_SIZE(newargs) != 2) {
4155 PyErr_Format(PyExc_ValueError,
4156 "__getnewargs_ex__ should return a tuple of "
4157 "length 2, not %zd", PyTuple_GET_SIZE(newargs));
4158 Py_DECREF(newargs);
4159 return -1;
4160 }
4161 *args = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(newargs, 0);
4162 Py_INCREF(*args);
4163 *kwargs = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(newargs, 1);
4164 Py_INCREF(*kwargs);
4165 Py_DECREF(newargs);
4166
4167 /* XXX We should perhaps allow None to be passed here. */
4168 if (!PyTuple_Check(*args)) {
4169 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
4170 "first item of the tuple returned by "
4171 "__getnewargs_ex__ must be a tuple, not '%.200s'",
4172 Py_TYPE(*args)->tp_name);
4173 Py_CLEAR(*args);
4174 Py_CLEAR(*kwargs);
4175 return -1;
4176 }
4177 if (!PyDict_Check(*kwargs)) {
4178 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
4179 "second item of the tuple returned by "
4180 "__getnewargs_ex__ must be a dict, not '%.200s'",
4181 Py_TYPE(*kwargs)->tp_name);
4182 Py_CLEAR(*args);
4183 Py_CLEAR(*kwargs);
4184 return -1;
4185 }
4186 return 0;
4187 } else if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
4188 return -1;
4189 }
4190
4191 /* The object does not have __getnewargs_ex__ so we fallback on using
4192 __getnewargs__ instead. */
4193 getnewargs = _PyObject_LookupSpecial(obj, &PyId___getnewargs__);
4194 if (getnewargs != NULL) {
4195 *args = _PyObject_CallNoArg(getnewargs);
4196 Py_DECREF(getnewargs);
4197 if (*args == NULL) {
4198 return -1;
4199 }
4200 if (!PyTuple_Check(*args)) {
4201 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
4202 "__getnewargs__ should return a tuple, "
4203 "not '%.200s'", Py_TYPE(*args)->tp_name);
4204 Py_CLEAR(*args);
4205 return -1;
4206 }
4207 *kwargs = NULL;
4208 return 0;
4209 } else if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
4210 return -1;
4211 }
4212
4213 /* The object does not have __getnewargs_ex__ and __getnewargs__. This may
4214 mean __new__ does not takes any arguments on this object, or that the
4215 object does not implement the reduce protocol for pickling or
4216 copying. */
4217 *args = NULL;
4218 *kwargs = NULL;
4219 return 0;
4220}
4221
4222static int
4223_PyObject_GetItemsIter(PyObject *obj, PyObject **listitems,
4224 PyObject **dictitems)
4225{
4226 if (listitems == NULL || dictitems == NULL) {
4227 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
4228 return -1;
4229 }
4230
4231 if (!PyList_Check(obj)) {
4232 *listitems = Py_None;
4233 Py_INCREF(*listitems);
4234 }
4235 else {
4236 *listitems = PyObject_GetIter(obj);
4237 if (*listitems == NULL)
4238 return -1;
4239 }
4240
4241 if (!PyDict_Check(obj)) {
4242 *dictitems = Py_None;
4243 Py_INCREF(*dictitems);
4244 }
4245 else {
4246 PyObject *items;
4247 _Py_IDENTIFIER(items);
4248
4249 items = _PyObject_CallMethodIdObjArgs(obj, &PyId_items, NULL);
4250 if (items == NULL) {
4251 Py_CLEAR(*listitems);
4252 return -1;
4253 }
4254 *dictitems = PyObject_GetIter(items);
4255 Py_DECREF(items);
4256 if (*dictitems == NULL) {
4257 Py_CLEAR(*listitems);
4258 return -1;
4259 }
4260 }
4261
4262 assert(*listitems != NULL && *dictitems != NULL);
4263
4264 return 0;
4265}

4267static PyObject *
4268reduce_newobj(PyObject *obj)
4269{
4270 PyObject *args = NULL, *kwargs = NULL;
4271 PyObject *copyreg;
4272 PyObject *newobj, *newargs, *state, *listitems, *dictitems;
4273 PyObject *result;
4274 int hasargs;
4275
4276 if (Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_new == NULL) {
4277 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
4278 "can't pickle %.200s objects",
4279 Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_name);
4280 return NULL;
4281 }
4282 if (_PyObject_GetNewArguments(obj, &args, &kwargs) < 0)
4283 return NULL;
4284
4285 copyreg = import_copyreg();
4286 if (copyreg == NULL) {
4287 Py_XDECREF(args);
4288 Py_XDECREF(kwargs);
4289 return NULL;
4290 }
4291 hasargs = (args != NULL);
4292 if (kwargs == NULL || PyDict_GET_SIZE(kwargs) == 0) {
4293 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__newobj__);
4294 PyObject *cls;
4295 Py_ssize_t i, n;
4296
4297 Py_XDECREF(kwargs);
4298 newobj = _PyObject_GetAttrId(copyreg, &PyId___newobj__);
4299 Py_DECREF(copyreg);
4300 if (newobj == NULL) {
4301 Py_XDECREF(args);
4302 return NULL;
4303 }
4304 n = args ? PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args) : 0;
4305 newargs = PyTuple_New(n+1);
4306 if (newargs == NULL) {
4307 Py_XDECREF(args);
4308 Py_DECREF(newobj);
4309 return NULL;
4310 }
4311 cls = (PyObject *) Py_TYPE(obj);
4312 Py_INCREF(cls);
4313 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(newargs, 0, cls);
4314 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
4315 PyObject *v = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(args, i);
4316 Py_INCREF(v);
4317 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(newargs, i+1, v);
4318 }
4319 Py_XDECREF(args);
4320 }
4321 else if (args != NULL) {
4322 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__newobj_ex__);
4323
4324 newobj = _PyObject_GetAttrId(copyreg, &PyId___newobj_ex__);
4325 Py_DECREF(copyreg);
4326 if (newobj == NULL) {
4327 Py_DECREF(args);
4328 Py_DECREF(kwargs);
4329 return NULL;
4330 }
4331 newargs = PyTuple_Pack(3, Py_TYPE(obj), args, kwargs);
4332 Py_DECREF(args);
4333 Py_DECREF(kwargs);
4334 if (newargs == NULL) {
4335 Py_DECREF(newobj);
4336 return NULL;
4337 }
4338 }
4339 else {
4340 /* args == NULL */
4341 Py_DECREF(kwargs);
4342 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
4343 return NULL;
4344 }
4345
4346 state = _PyObject_GetState(obj,
4347 !hasargs && !PyList_Check(obj) && !PyDict_Check(obj));
4348 if (state == NULL) {
4349 Py_DECREF(newobj);
4350 Py_DECREF(newargs);
4351 return NULL;
4352 }
4353 if (_PyObject_GetItemsIter(obj, &listitems, &dictitems) < 0) {
4354 Py_DECREF(newobj);
4355 Py_DECREF(newargs);
4356 Py_DECREF(state);
4357 return NULL;
4358 }
4359
4360 result = PyTuple_Pack(5, newobj, newargs, state, listitems, dictitems);
4361 Py_DECREF(newobj);
4362 Py_DECREF(newargs);
4363 Py_DECREF(state);
4364 Py_DECREF(listitems);
4365 Py_DECREF(dictitems);
4366 return result;
4367}
4368
4369/*
4370 * There were two problems when object.__reduce__ and object.__reduce_ex__
4371 * were implemented in the same function:
4372 * - trying to pickle an object with a custom __reduce__ method that
4373 * fell back to object.__reduce__ in certain circumstances led to
4374 * infinite recursion at Python level and eventual RecursionError.
4375 * - Pickling objects that lied about their type by overwriting the
4376 * __class__ descriptor could lead to infinite recursion at C level
4377 * and eventual segfault.
4378 *
4379 * Because of backwards compatibility, the two methods still have to
4380 * behave in the same way, even if this is not required by the pickle
4381 * protocol. This common functionality was moved to the _common_reduce
4382 * function.
4383 */
4384static PyObject *
4385_common_reduce(PyObject *self, int proto)
4386{
4387 PyObject *copyreg, *res;
4388
4389 if (proto >= 2)
4390 return reduce_newobj(self);
4391
4392 copyreg = import_copyreg();
4393 if (!copyreg)
4394 return NULL;
4395
4396 res = PyObject_CallMethod(copyreg, "_reduce_ex", "Oi", self, proto);
4397 Py_DECREF(copyreg);
4398
4399 return res;
4400}

4461 }

4537/* __dir__ for generic objects: returns __dict__, __class__,
4538 and recursively up the __class__.__bases__ chain.
4539*/
4540/*[clinic input]
4541object.__dir__
4542
4543Default dir() implementation.
4544[clinic start generated code]*/
4545
4546static PyObject *
4547object___dir___impl(PyObject *self)
4548/*[clinic end generated code: output=66dd48ea62f26c90 input=0a89305bec669b10]*/
4549{
4550 PyObject *result = NULL;
4551 PyObject *dict = NULL;
4552 PyObject *itsclass = NULL;
4553
4554 /* Get __dict__ (which may or may not be a real dict...) */
4555 dict = _PyObject_GetAttrId(self, &PyId___dict__);
4556 if (dict == NULL) {
4557 PyErr_Clear();
4558 dict = PyDict_New();
4559 }
4560 else if (!PyDict_Check(dict)) {
4561 Py_DECREF(dict);
4562 dict = PyDict_New();
4563 }
4564 else {
4565 /* Copy __dict__ to avoid mutating it. */
4566 PyObject *temp = PyDict_Copy(dict);
4567 Py_DECREF(dict);
4568 dict = temp;
4569 }
4570
4571 if (dict == NULL)
4572 goto error;
4573
4574 /* Merge in attrs reachable from its class. */
4575 itsclass = _PyObject_GetAttrId(self, &PyId___class__);
4576 if (itsclass == NULL)
4577 /* XXX(tomer): Perhaps fall back to obj->ob_type if no
4578 __class__ exists? */
4579 PyErr_Clear();
4580 else if (merge_class_dict(dict, itsclass) != 0)
4581 goto error;
4582
4583 result = PyDict_Keys(dict);
4584 /* fall through */
4585error:
4586 Py_XDECREF(itsclass);
4587 Py_XDECREF(dict);
4588 return result;
4589}

4648/* Add the methods from tp_methods to the __dict__ in a type object */
4649
4650static int
4651add_methods(PyTypeObject *type, PyMethodDef *meth)
4652{
4653 PyObject *dict = type->tp_dict;
4654
4655 for (; meth->ml_name != NULL; meth++) {
4656 PyObject *descr;
4657 int err;
4658 int isdescr = 1;
4659 if (PyDict_GetItemString(dict, meth->ml_name) &&
4660 !(meth->ml_flags & METH_COEXIST))
4661 continue;
4662 if (meth->ml_flags & METH_CLASS) {
4663 if (meth->ml_flags & METH_STATIC) {
4664 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,
4665 "method cannot be both class and static");
4666 return -1;
4667 }
4668 descr = PyDescr_NewClassMethod(type, meth);
4669 }
4670 else if (meth->ml_flags & METH_STATIC) {
4671 PyObject *cfunc = PyCFunction_NewEx(meth, (PyObject*)type, NULL);
4672 if (cfunc == NULL)
4673 return -1;
4674 descr = PyStaticMethod_New(cfunc);
4675 isdescr = 0; // PyStaticMethod is not PyDescrObject
4676 Py_DECREF(cfunc);
4677 }
4678 else {
4679 descr = PyDescr_NewMethod(type, meth);
4680 }
4681 if (descr == NULL)
4682 return -1;
4683 if (isdescr) {
4684 err = PyDict_SetItem(dict, PyDescr_NAME(descr), descr);
4685 }
4686 else {
4687 err = PyDict_SetItemString(dict, meth->ml_name, descr);
4688 }
4689 Py_DECREF(descr);
4690 if (err < 0)
4691 return -1;
4692 }
4693 return 0;
4694}

4739static void
4740inherit_special(PyTypeObject *type, PyTypeObject *base)
4741{
4742
4743 /* Copying basicsize is connected to the GC flags */
4744 if (!(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC) &&
4745 (base->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC) &&
4746 (!type->tp_traverse && !type->tp_clear)) {
4747 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC;
4748 if (type->tp_traverse == NULL)
4749 type->tp_traverse = base->tp_traverse;
4750 if (type->tp_clear == NULL)
4751 type->tp_clear = base->tp_clear;
4752 }
4753 {
4754 /* The condition below could use some explanation.
4755 It appears that tp_new is not inherited for static types
4756 whose base class is 'object'; this seems to be a precaution
4757 so that old extension types don't suddenly become
4758 callable (object.__new__ wouldn't insure the invariants
4759 that the extension type's own factory function ensures).
4760 Heap types, of course, are under our control, so they do
4761 inherit tp_new; static extension types that specify some
4762 other built-in type as the default also
4763 inherit object.__new__. */
4764 if (base != &PyBaseObject_Type ||
4765 (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)) {
4766 if (type->tp_new == NULL)
4767 type->tp_new = base->tp_new;
4768 }
4769 }
4770 if (type->tp_basicsize == 0)
4771 type->tp_basicsize = base->tp_basicsize;
4772
4773 /* Copy other non-function slots */
4774
4775#undef COPYVAL
4776#define COPYVAL(SLOT) \
4777 if (type->SLOT == 0) type->SLOT = base->SLOT
4778
4779 COPYVAL(tp_itemsize);
4780 COPYVAL(tp_weaklistoffset);
4781 COPYVAL(tp_dictoffset);
4782
4783 /* Setup fast subclass flags */
4784 if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, (PyTypeObject*)PyExc_BaseException))
4785 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_BASE_EXC_SUBCLASS;
4786 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, &PyType_Type))
4787 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_TYPE_SUBCLASS;
4788 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, &PyLong_Type))
4789 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_LONG_SUBCLASS;
4790 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, &PyBytes_Type))
4791 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_BYTES_SUBCLASS;
4792 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, &PyUnicode_Type))
4793 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_UNICODE_SUBCLASS;
4794 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, &PyTuple_Type))
4795 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_TUPLE_SUBCLASS;
4796 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, &PyList_Type))
4797 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_LIST_SUBCLASS;
4798 else if (PyType_IsSubtype(base, &PyDict_Type))
4799 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_DICT_SUBCLASS;
4800}

4816static void
4817inherit_slots(PyTypeObject *type, PyTypeObject *base)
4818{
4819 PyTypeObject *basebase;
4820
4821#undef SLOTDEFINED
4822#undef COPYSLOT
4823#undef COPYNUM
4824#undef COPYSEQ
4825#undef COPYMAP
4826#undef COPYBUF
4827
4828#define SLOTDEFINED(SLOT) \
4829 (base->SLOT != 0 && \
4830 (basebase == NULL || base->SLOT != basebase->SLOT))
4831
4832#define COPYSLOT(SLOT) \
4833 if (!type->SLOT && SLOTDEFINED(SLOT)) type->SLOT = base->SLOT
4834
4835#define COPYASYNC(SLOT) COPYSLOT(tp_as_async->SLOT)
4836#define COPYNUM(SLOT) COPYSLOT(tp_as_number->SLOT)
4837#define COPYSEQ(SLOT) COPYSLOT(tp_as_sequence->SLOT)
4838#define COPYMAP(SLOT) COPYSLOT(tp_as_mapping->SLOT)
4839#define COPYBUF(SLOT) COPYSLOT(tp_as_buffer->SLOT)
4840
4841 /* This won't inherit indirect slots (from tp_as_number etc.)
4842 if type doesn't provide the space. */
4843

4847 basebase = NULL;

4880 COPYNUM(nb_index);
4881 COPYNUM(nb_matrix_multiply);
4882 COPYNUM(nb_inplace_matrix_multiply);
4883 }

4885 if (type->tp_as_async != NULL && base->tp_as_async != NULL) {
4886 basebase = base->tp_base;
4887 if (basebase->tp_as_async == NULL)
4888 basebase = NULL;
4889 COPYASYNC(am_await);
4890 COPYASYNC(am_aiter);
4891 COPYASYNC(am_anext);

4895 basebase = base->tp_base;
4896 if (basebase->tp_as_sequence == NULL)
4897 basebase = NULL;
4898 COPYSEQ(sq_length);
4899 COPYSEQ(sq_concat);
4900 COPYSEQ(sq_repeat);
4901 COPYSEQ(sq_item);
4902 COPYSEQ(sq_ass_item);

4921 COPYBUF(bf_getbuffer);
4922 COPYBUF(bf_releasebuffer);

4929 type->tp_getattr = base->tp_getattr;
4930 type->tp_getattro = base->tp_getattro;
4931 }

4933 type->tp_setattr = base->tp_setattr;
4934 type->tp_setattro = base->tp_setattro;
4935 }
4936 /* tp_reserved is ignored */
4937 COPYSLOT(tp_repr);
4938 /* tp_hash see tp_richcompare */
4939 COPYSLOT(tp_call);
4940 COPYSLOT(tp_str);
4941 {
4942 /* Copy comparison-related slots only when
4943 not overriding them anywhere */

4945 type->tp_hash == NULL &&
4946 !overrides_hash(type))
4947 {
4948 type->tp_richcompare = base->tp_richcompare;
4949 type->tp_hash = base->tp_hash;
4950 }
4951 }
4952 {
4953 COPYSLOT(tp_iter);
4954 COPYSLOT(tp_iternext);
4955 }
4956 {

4958 COPYSLOT(tp_descr_set);
4959 COPYSLOT(tp_dictoffset);
4960 COPYSLOT(tp_init);

4962 COPYSLOT(tp_is_gc);
4963 if ((type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_FINALIZE) &&
4964 (base->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_FINALIZE)) {
4965 COPYSLOT(tp_finalize);
4966 }
4967 if ((type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC) ==
4968 (base->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HAVE_GC)) {
4969 /* They agree about gc. */
4970 COPYSLOT(tp_free);
4971 }

4973 type->tp_free == NULL &&
4974 base->tp_free == PyObject_Free) {

4976 * tp_free function when a derived class adds gc,
4977 * didn't define tp_free, and the base uses the
4978 * default non-gc tp_free.
4979 */
4980 type->tp_free = PyObject_GC_Del;
4981 }
4982 /* else they didn't agree about gc, and there isn't something
4983 * obvious to be done -- the type is on its own.
4984 */
4985 }

4989
4990int
4991PyType_Ready(PyTypeObject *type)
4992{
4993 PyObject *dict, *bases;
4994 PyTypeObject *base;
4995 Py_ssize_t i, n;
4996
4997 if (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_READY) {
4998 assert(_PyType_CheckConsistency(type));
4999 return 0;
5000 }
5001 assert((type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_READYING) == 0);
5002
5003 type->tp_flags |= Py_TPFLAGS_READYING;
5004
5005#ifdef Py_TRACE_REFS
5006 /* PyType_Ready is the closest thing we have to a choke point
5007 * for type objects, so is the best place I can think of to try
5008 * to get type objects into the doubly-linked list of all objects.
5009 * Still, not all type objects go thru PyType_Ready.
5010 */
5011 _Py_AddToAllObjects((PyObject *)type, 0);
5012#endif
5013
5014 if (type->tp_name == NULL) {
5015 PyErr_Format(PyExc_SystemError,
5016 "Type does not define the tp_name field.");
5017 goto error;
5018 }
5019
5020 /* Initialize tp_base (defaults to BaseObject unless that's us) */
5021 base = type->tp_base;
5022 if (base == NULL && type != &PyBaseObject_Type) {
5023 base = type->tp_base = &PyBaseObject_Type;
5024 Py_INCREF(base);
5025 }
5026
5027 /* Now the only way base can still be NULL is if type is
5028 * &PyBaseObject_Type.
5029 */
5030
5031 /* Initialize the base class */
5032 if (base != NULL && base->tp_dict == NULL) {
5033 if (PyType_Ready(base) < 0)
5034 goto error;
5035 }
5036
5037 /* Initialize ob_type if NULL. This means extensions that want to be
5038 compilable separately on Windows can call PyType_Ready() instead of
5039 initializing the ob_type field of their type objects. */
5040 /* The test for base != NULL is really unnecessary, since base is only
5041 NULL when type is &PyBaseObject_Type, and we know its ob_type is
5042 not NULL (it's initialized to &PyType_Type). But coverity doesn't
5043 know that. */
5044 if (Py_TYPE(type) == NULL && base != NULL)
5045 Py_TYPE(type) = Py_TYPE(base);
5046
5047 /* Initialize tp_bases */
5048 bases = type->tp_bases;
5049 if (bases == NULL) {
5050 if (base == NULL)
5051 bases = PyTuple_New(0);
5052 else
5053 bases = PyTuple_Pack(1, base);
5054 if (bases == NULL)
5055 goto error;
5056 type->tp_bases = bases;
5057 }
5058
5059 /* Initialize tp_dict */
5060 dict = type->tp_dict;
5061 if (dict == NULL) {
5062 dict = PyDict_New();
5063 if (dict == NULL)
5064 goto error;
5065 type->tp_dict = dict;
5066 }
5067
5068 /* Add type-specific descriptors to tp_dict */
5069 if (add_operators(type) < 0)
5070 goto error;
5071 if (type->tp_methods != NULL) {
5072 if (add_methods(type, type->tp_methods) < 0)
5073 goto error;
5074 }
5075 if (type->tp_members != NULL) {
5076 if (add_members(type, type->tp_members) < 0)
5077 goto error;
5078 }
5079 if (type->tp_getset != NULL) {
5080 if (add_getset(type, type->tp_getset) < 0)
5081 goto error;
5082 }
5083
5084 /* Calculate method resolution order */
5085 if (mro_internal(type, NULL) < 0)
5086 goto error;
5087
5088 /* Inherit special flags from dominant base */
5089 if (type->tp_base != NULL)
5090 inherit_special(type, type->tp_base);
5091
5092 /* Initialize tp_dict properly */
5093 bases = type->tp_mro;
5094 assert(bases != NULL);
5095 assert(PyTuple_Check(bases));
5096 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
5097 for (i = 1; i < n; i++) {
5098 PyObject *b = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
5099 if (PyType_Check(b))
5100 inherit_slots(type, (PyTypeObject *)b);
5101 }
5102
5103 /* All bases of statically allocated type should be statically allocated */
5104 if (!(type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE))
5105 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
5106 PyObject *b = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
5107 if (PyType_Check(b) &&
5108 (((PyTypeObject *)b)->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)) {
5109 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
5110 "type '%.100s' is not dynamically allocated but "
5111 "its base type '%.100s' is dynamically allocated",
5112 type->tp_name, ((PyTypeObject *)b)->tp_name);
5113 goto error;
5114 }
5115 }
5116
5117 /* Sanity check for tp_free. */
5118 if (PyType_IS_GC(type) && (type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_BASETYPE) &&
5119 (type->tp_free == NULL || type->tp_free == PyObject_Del)) {
5120 /* This base class needs to call tp_free, but doesn't have
5121 * one, or its tp_free is for non-gc'ed objects.
5122 */
5123 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError, "type '%.100s' participates in "
5124 "gc and is a base type but has inappropriate "
5125 "tp_free slot",
5126 type->tp_name);
5127 goto error;
5128 }
5129
5130 /* if the type dictionary doesn't contain a __doc__, set it from
5131 the tp_doc slot.
5132 */
5133 if (_PyDict_GetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___doc__) == NULL) {
5134 if (type->tp_doc != NULL) {
5135 const char *old_doc = _PyType_DocWithoutSignature(type->tp_name,
5136 type->tp_doc);
5137 PyObject *doc = PyUnicode_FromString(old_doc);
5138 if (doc == NULL)
5139 goto error;
5140 if (_PyDict_SetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___doc__, doc) < 0) {
5141 Py_DECREF(doc);
5142 goto error;
5143 }
5144 Py_DECREF(doc);
5145 } else {
5146 if (_PyDict_SetItemId(type->tp_dict,
5147 &PyId___doc__, Py_None) < 0)
5148 goto error;
5149 }
5150 }
5151
5152 /* Hack for tp_hash and __hash__.
5153 If after all that, tp_hash is still NULL, and __hash__ is not in
5154 tp_dict, set tp_hash to PyObject_HashNotImplemented and
5155 tp_dict['__hash__'] equal to None.
5156 This signals that __hash__ is not inherited.
5157 */
5158 if (type->tp_hash == NULL) {
5159 if (_PyDict_GetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___hash__) == NULL) {
5160 if (_PyDict_SetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___hash__, Py_None) < 0)
5161 goto error;
5162 type->tp_hash = PyObject_HashNotImplemented;
5163 }
5164 }
5165
5166 /* Some more special stuff */
5167 base = type->tp_base;
5168 if (base != NULL) {
5169 if (type->tp_as_async == NULL)
5170 type->tp_as_async = base->tp_as_async;
5171 if (type->tp_as_number == NULL)
5172 type->tp_as_number = base->tp_as_number;
5173 if (type->tp_as_sequence == NULL)
5174 type->tp_as_sequence = base->tp_as_sequence;
5175 if (type->tp_as_mapping == NULL)
5176 type->tp_as_mapping = base->tp_as_mapping;
5177 if (type->tp_as_buffer == NULL)
5178 type->tp_as_buffer = base->tp_as_buffer;
5179 }
5180
5181 /* Link into each base class's list of subclasses */
5182 bases = type->tp_bases;
5183 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases);
5184 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
5185 PyObject *b = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
5186 if (PyType_Check(b) &&
5187 add_subclass((PyTypeObject *)b, type) < 0)
5188 goto error;
5189 }
5190
5191 /* All done -- set the ready flag */
5192 type->tp_flags =
5193 (type->tp_flags & ~Py_TPFLAGS_READYING) | Py_TPFLAGS_READY;
5194 assert(_PyType_CheckConsistency(type));
5195 return 0;
5196
5197 error:
5198 type->tp_flags &= ~Py_TPFLAGS_READYING;
5199 return -1;
5200}
5201
5202static int
5203add_subclass(PyTypeObject *base, PyTypeObject *type)
5204{
5205 int result = -1;
5206 PyObject *dict, *key, *newobj;
5207
5208 dict = base->tp_subclasses;
5209 if (dict == NULL) {
5210 base->tp_subclasses = dict = PyDict_New();
5211 if (dict == NULL)
5212 return -1;
5213 }
5214 assert(PyDict_CheckExact(dict));
5215 key = PyLong_FromVoidPtr((void *) type);
5216 if (key == NULL)
5217 return -1;
5218 newobj = PyWeakref_NewRef((PyObject *)type, NULL);
5219 if (newobj != NULL) {
5220 result = PyDict_SetItem(dict, key, newobj);
5221 Py_DECREF(newobj);
5222 }
5223 Py_DECREF(key);
5224 return result;
5225}

5227static int
5228add_all_subclasses(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *bases)
5229{
5230 int res = 0;
5231
5232 if (bases) {
5233 Py_ssize_t i;
5234 for (i = 0; i < PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases); i++) {
5235 PyObject *base = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
5236 if (PyType_Check(base) &&
5237 add_subclass((PyTypeObject*)base, type) < 0)
5238 res = -1;
5239 }
5240 }
5241
5242 return res;
5243}
5244
5245static void
5246remove_subclass(PyTypeObject *base, PyTypeObject *type)
5247{
5248 PyObject *dict, *key;
5249
5250 dict = base->tp_subclasses;
5251 if (dict == NULL) {
5252 return;
5253 }
5254 assert(PyDict_CheckExact(dict));
5255 key = PyLong_FromVoidPtr((void *) type);
5256 if (key == NULL || PyDict_DelItem(dict, key)) {
5257 /* This can happen if the type initialization errored out before
5258 the base subclasses were updated (e.g. a non-str __qualname__
5259 was passed in the type dict). */
5260 PyErr_Clear();
5261 }
5262 Py_XDECREF(key);
5263}
5264
5265static void
5266remove_all_subclasses(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *bases)
5267{
5268 if (bases) {
5269 Py_ssize_t i;
5270 for (i = 0; i < PyTuple_GET_SIZE(bases); i++) {
5271 PyObject *base = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(bases, i);
5272 if (PyType_Check(base))
5273 remove_subclass((PyTypeObject*) base, type);
5274 }
5275 }
5276}

5278static int
5279check_num_args(PyObject *ob, int n)
5280{
5281 if (!PyTuple_CheckExact(ob)) {
5282 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_SystemError,
5283 "PyArg_UnpackTuple() argument list is not a tuple");
5284 return 0;
5285 }
5286 if (n == PyTuple_GET_SIZE(ob))
5287 return 1;
5288 PyErr_Format(
5289 PyExc_TypeError,
5290 "expected %d arguments, got %zd", n, PyTuple_GET_SIZE(ob));
5291 return 0;
5292}

5294/* Generic wrappers for overloadable 'operators' such as __getitem__ */
5295
5296/* There's a wrapper *function* for each distinct function typedef used
5297 for type object slots (e.g. binaryfunc, ternaryfunc, etc.). There's a
5298 wrapper *table* for each distinct operation (e.g. __len__, __add__).
5299 Most tables have only one entry; the tables for binary operators have two
5300 entries, one regular and one with reversed arguments. */
5301
5302static PyObject *
5303wrap_lenfunc(PyObject *self, PyObject *args, void *wrapped)
5304{
5305 lenfunc func = (lenfunc)wrapped;
5306 Py_ssize_t res;
5307
5308 if (!check_num_args(args, 0))
5309 return NULL;
5310 res = (*func)(self);
5311 if (res == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
5312 return NULL;
5313 return PyLong_FromLong((long)res);
5314}

5410

5419static Py_ssize_t
5420getindex(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)
5421{
5422 Py_ssize_t i;
5423
5424 i = PyNumber_AsSsize_t(arg, PyExc_OverflowError);
5425 if (i == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
5426 return -1;
5427 if (i < 0) {
5428 PySequenceMethods *sq = Py_TYPE(self)->tp_as_sequence;
5429 if (sq && sq->sq_length) {
5430 Py_ssize_t n = (*sq->sq_length)(self);
5431 if (n < 0) {
5432 assert(PyErr_Occurred());
5433 return -1;
5434 }
5435 i += n;
5436 }
5437 }
5438 return i;
5439}

5445 PyObject *arg;
5446 Py_ssize_t i;

5449 arg = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(args, 0);
5450 i = getindex(self, arg);
5451 if (i == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
5452 return NULL;
5453 return (*func)(self, i);
5454 }
5455 check_num_args(args, 1);
5456 assert(PyErr_Occurred());
5457 return NULL;
5458}

5548/* Helper to check for object.__setattr__ or __delattr__ applied to a type.
5549 This is called the Carlo Verre hack after its discoverer. */
5550static int
5551hackcheck(PyObject *self, setattrofunc func, const char *what)
5552{
5553 PyTypeObject *type = Py_TYPE(self);
5554 while (type && type->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE)
5555 type = type->tp_base;
5556 /* If type is NULL now, this is a really weird type.
5557 In the spirit of backwards compatibility (?), just shut up. */
5558 if (type && type->tp_setattro != func) {
5559 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
5560 "can't apply this %s to %s object",
5561 what,
5562 type->tp_name);
5563 return 0;
5564 }
5565 return 1;
5566}

5574

5576 return NULL;

5740static PyObject *
5741tp_new_wrapper(PyObject *self, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
5742{
5743 PyTypeObject *type, *subtype, *staticbase;
5744 PyObject *arg0, *res;
5745
5746 if (self == NULL || !PyType_Check(self))
5747 Py_FatalError("__new__() called with non-type 'self'");
5748 type = (PyTypeObject *)self;
5749 if (!PyTuple_Check(args) || PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args) < 1) {
5750 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
5751 "%s.__new__(): not enough arguments",
5752 type->tp_name);
5753 return NULL;
5754 }
5755 arg0 = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(args, 0);
5756 if (!PyType_Check(arg0)) {
5757 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
5758 "%s.__new__(X): X is not a type object (%s)",
5759 type->tp_name,
5760 Py_TYPE(arg0)->tp_name);
5761 return NULL;
5762 }
5763 subtype = (PyTypeObject *)arg0;
5764 if (!PyType_IsSubtype(subtype, type)) {
5765 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
5766 "%s.__new__(%s): %s is not a subtype of %s",
5767 type->tp_name,
5768 subtype->tp_name,
5769 subtype->tp_name,
5770 type->tp_name);
5771 return NULL;
5772 }
5773
5774 /* Check that the use doesn't do something silly and unsafe like
5775 object.__new__(dict). To do this, we check that the
5776 most derived base that's not a heap type is this type. */
5777 staticbase = subtype;
5778 while (staticbase && (staticbase->tp_new == slot_tp_new))
5779 staticbase = staticbase->tp_base;
5780 /* If staticbase is NULL now, it is a really weird type.
5781 In the spirit of backwards compatibility (?), just shut up. */
5782 if (staticbase && staticbase->tp_new != type->tp_new) {
5783 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
5784 "%s.__new__(%s) is not safe, use %s.__new__()",
5785 type->tp_name,
5786 subtype->tp_name,
5787 staticbase->tp_name);
5788 return NULL;
5789 }
5790
5791 args = PyTuple_GetSlice(args, 1, PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args));
5792 if (args == NULL)
5793 return NULL;
5794 res = type->tp_new(subtype, args, kwds);
5795 Py_DECREF(args);
5796 return res;
5797}
5798
5799static struct PyMethodDef tp_new_methoddef[] = {
5800 {"__new__", (PyCFunction)tp_new_wrapper, METH_VARARGS|METH_KEYWORDS,
5801 PyDoc_STR("__new__($type, *args, **kwargs)\n--\n\n"
5802 "Create and return a new object. "
5803 "See help(type) for accurate signature.")},
5804 {0}
5805};
5806
5807static int
5808add_tp_new_wrapper(PyTypeObject *type)
5809{
5810 PyObject *func;
5811
5812 if (_PyDict_GetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___new__) != NULL)
5813 return 0;
5814 func = PyCFunction_NewEx(tp_new_methoddef, (PyObject *)type, NULL);
5815 if (func == NULL)
5816 return -1;
5817 if (_PyDict_SetItemId(type->tp_dict, &PyId___new__, func)) {
5818 Py_DECREF(func);
5819 return -1;
5820 }
5821 Py_DECREF(func);
5822 return 0;
5823}

5845/* Boolean helper for SLOT1BINFULL().
5846 right.__class__ is a nontrivial subclass of left.__class__. */
5847static int
5848method_is_overloaded(PyObject *left, PyObject *right, struct _Py_Identifier *name)
5849{
5850 PyObject *a, *b;
5851 int ok;
5852
5853 b = _PyObject_GetAttrId((PyObject *)(Py_TYPE(right)), name);
5854 if (b == NULL) {
5855 PyErr_Clear();
5856 /* If right doesn't have it, it's not overloaded */
5857 return 0;
5858 }
5859
5860 a = _PyObject_GetAttrId((PyObject *)(Py_TYPE(left)), name);
5861 if (a == NULL) {
5862 PyErr_Clear();
5863 Py_DECREF(b);
5864 /* If right has it but left doesn't, it's overloaded */
5865 return 1;
5866 }
5867
5868 ok = PyObject_RichCompareBool(a, b, Py_NE);
5869 Py_DECREF(a);
5870 Py_DECREF(b);
5871 if (ok < 0) {
5872 PyErr_Clear();
5873 return 0;
5874 }
5875
5876 return ok;
5877}

5880#define SLOT1BINFULL(FUNCNAME, TESTFUNC, SLOTNAME, OPSTR, ROPSTR) \
5881static PyObject * \
5882FUNCNAME(PyObject *self, PyObject *other) \
5883{ \
5884 PyObject* stack[1]; \
5885 _Py_static_string(op_id, OPSTR); \
5886 _Py_static_string(rop_id, ROPSTR); \
5887 int do_other = Py_TYPE(self) != Py_TYPE(other) && \
5888 Py_TYPE(other)->tp_as_number != NULL && \
5889 Py_TYPE(other)->tp_as_number->SLOTNAME == TESTFUNC; \
5890 if (Py_TYPE(self)->tp_as_number != NULL && \
5891 Py_TYPE(self)->tp_as_number->SLOTNAME == TESTFUNC) { \
5892 PyObject *r; \
5893 if (do_other && \
5894 PyType_IsSubtype(Py_TYPE(other), Py_TYPE(self)) && \
5895 method_is_overloaded(self, other, &rop_id)) { \
5896 stack[0] = self; \
5897 r = call_maybe(other, &rop_id, stack, 1); \
5898 if (r != Py_NotImplemented) \
5899 return r; \
5900 Py_DECREF(r); \
5901 do_other = 0; \
5902 } \
5903 stack[0] = other; \
5904 r = call_maybe(self, &op_id, stack, 1); \
5905 if (r != Py_NotImplemented || \
5906 Py_TYPE(other) == Py_TYPE(self)) \
5907 return r; \
5908 Py_DECREF(r); \
5909 } \
5910 if (do_other) { \
5911 stack[0] = self; \
5912 return call_maybe(other, &rop_id, stack, 1); \
5913 } \
5914 Py_RETURN_NOTIMPLEMENTED; \
5915}

5920static Py_ssize_t
5921slot_sq_length(PyObject *self)
5922{
5923 PyObject *res = call_method(self, &PyId___len__, NULL, 0);
5924 Py_ssize_t len;
5925
5926 if (res == NULL)
5927 return -1;
5928
5929 Py_SETREF(res, PyNumber_Index(res));
5930 if (res == NULL)
5931 return -1;
5932
5933 assert(PyLong_Check(res));
5934 if (Py_SIZE(res) < 0) {
5935 Py_DECREF(res);
5936 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,
5937 "__len__() should return >= 0");
5938 return -1;
5939 }
5940
5941 len = PyNumber_AsSsize_t(res, PyExc_OverflowError);
5942 assert(len >= 0 || PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_OverflowError));
5943 Py_DECREF(res);
5944 return len;
5945}

5949{
5950 PyObject *retval;

5952 PyObject *ival = PyLong_FromSsize_t(i);
5953 if (ival == NULL) {
5954 return NULL;
5955 }
5956 args[0] = ival;
5957 retval = call_method(self, &PyId___getitem__, args, 1);
5958 Py_DECREF(ival);
5959 return retval;
5960}

5962static int
5963slot_sq_ass_item(PyObject *self, Py_ssize_t index, PyObject *value)
5964{
5965 PyObject *stack[2];
5966 PyObject *res;
5967 PyObject *index_obj;
5968
5969 index_obj = PyLong_FromSsize_t(index);
5970 if (index_obj == NULL) {
5971 return -1;
5972 }
5973
5974 stack[0] = index_obj;
5975 if (value == NULL) {
5976 res = call_method(self, &PyId___delitem__, stack, 1);
5977 }
5978 else {
5979 stack[1] = value;
5980 res = call_method(self, &PyId___setitem__, stack, 2);
5981 }
5982 Py_DECREF(index_obj);
5983
5984 if (res == NULL) {
5985 return -1;
5986 }
5987 Py_DECREF(res);
5988 return 0;
5989}

5991static int
5992slot_sq_contains(PyObject *self, PyObject *value)
5993{
5994 PyObject *func, *res;
5995 int result = -1, unbound;
5996 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__contains__);
5997
5998 func = lookup_maybe_method(self, &PyId___contains__, &unbound);
5999 if (func == Py_None) {
6000 Py_DECREF(func);
6001 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
6002 "'%.200s' object is not a container",
6003 Py_TYPE(self)->tp_name);
6004 return -1;
6005 }
6006 if (func != NULL) {
6007 PyObject *args[1] = {value};
6008 res = call_unbound(unbound, func, self, args, 1);
6009 Py_DECREF(func);
6010 if (res != NULL) {
6011 result = PyObject_IsTrue(res);
6012 Py_DECREF(res);
6013 }
6014 }
6015 else if (! PyErr_Occurred()) {
6016 /* Possible results: -1 and 1 */
6017 result = (int)_PySequence_IterSearch(self, value,
6018 PY_ITERSEARCH_CONTAINS);
6019 }
6020 return result;
6021}

6060static PyObject *
6061slot_nb_power(PyObject *self, PyObject *other, PyObject *modulus)
6062{
6063 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__pow__);
6064
6065 if (modulus == Py_None)
6066 return slot_nb_power_binary(self, other);
6067 /* Three-arg power doesn't use __rpow__. But ternary_op
6068 can call this when the second argument's type uses
6069 slot_nb_power, so check before calling self.__pow__. */
6070 if (Py_TYPE(self)->tp_as_number != NULL &&
6071 Py_TYPE(self)->tp_as_number->nb_power == slot_nb_power) {
6072 PyObject* stack[2] = {other, modulus};
6073 return call_method(self, &PyId___pow__, stack, 2);
6074 }
6075 Py_RETURN_NOTIMPLEMENTED;
6076}

6082static int
6083slot_nb_bool(PyObject *self)
6084{
6085 PyObject *func, *value;
6086 int result, unbound;
6087 int using_len = 0;
6088 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__bool__);
6089
6090 func = lookup_maybe_method(self, &PyId___bool__, &unbound);
6091 if (func == NULL) {
6092 if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
6093 return -1;
6094 }
6095
6096 func = lookup_maybe_method(self, &PyId___len__, &unbound);
6097 if (func == NULL) {
6098 if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
6099 return -1;
6100 }
6101 return 1;
6102 }
6103 using_len = 1;
6104 }
6105
6106 value = call_unbound_noarg(unbound, func, self);
6107 if (value == NULL) {
6108 goto error;
6109 }
6110
6111 if (using_len) {
6112 /* bool type enforced by slot_nb_len */
6113 result = PyObject_IsTrue(value);
6114 }
6115 else if (PyBool_Check(value)) {
6116 result = PyObject_IsTrue(value);
6117 }
6118 else {
6119 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
6120 "__bool__ should return "
6121 "bool, returned %s",
6122 Py_TYPE(value)->tp_name);
6123 result = -1;
6124 }
6125
6126 Py_DECREF(value);
6127 Py_DECREF(func);
6128 return result;
6129
6130error:
6131 Py_DECREF(func);
6132 return -1;
6133}

6197static Py_hash_t
6198slot_tp_hash(PyObject *self)
6199{
6200 PyObject *func, *res;
6201 Py_ssize_t h;
6202 int unbound;
6203
6204 func = lookup_maybe_method(self, &PyId___hash__, &unbound);
6205
6206 if (func == Py_None) {
6207 Py_DECREF(func);
6208 func = NULL;
6209 }
6210
6211 if (func == NULL) {
6212 return PyObject_HashNotImplemented(self);
6213 }
6214
6215 res = call_unbound_noarg(unbound, func, self);
6216 Py_DECREF(func);
6217 if (res == NULL)
6218 return -1;
6219
6220 if (!PyLong_Check(res)) {
6221 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
6222 "__hash__ method should return an integer");
6223 return -1;
6224 }
6225 /* Transform the PyLong `res` to a Py_hash_t `h`. For an existing
6226 hashable Python object x, hash(x) will always lie within the range of
6227 Py_hash_t. Therefore our transformation must preserve values that
6228 already lie within this range, to ensure that if x.__hash__() returns
6229 hash(y) then hash(x) == hash(y). */
6230 h = PyLong_AsSsize_t(res);
6231 if (h == -1 && PyErr_Occurred()) {
6232 /* res was not within the range of a Py_hash_t, so we're free to
6233 use any sufficiently bit-mixing transformation;
6234 long.__hash__ will do nicely. */
6235 PyErr_Clear();
6236 h = PyLong_Type.tp_hash(res);
6237 }
6238 /* -1 is reserved for errors. */
6239 if (h == -1)
6240 h = -2;
6241 Py_DECREF(res);
6242 return h;
6243}

6245static PyObject *
6246slot_tp_call(PyObject *self, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
6247{
6248 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__call__);
6249 int unbound;
6250 PyObject *meth = lookup_method(self, &PyId___call__, &unbound);
6251 PyObject *res;
6252
6253 if (meth == NULL)
6254 return NULL;
6255
6256 if (unbound) {
6257 res = _PyObject_Call_Prepend(meth, self, args, kwds);
6258 }
6259 else {
6260 res = PyObject_Call(meth, args, kwds);
6261 }
6262
6263 Py_DECREF(meth);
6264 return res;
6265}

6267/* There are two slot dispatch functions for tp_getattro.
6268
6269 - slot_tp_getattro() is used when __getattribute__ is overridden
6270 but no __getattr__ hook is present;
6271
6272 - slot_tp_getattr_hook() is used when a __getattr__ hook is present.
6273
6274 The code in update_one_slot() always installs slot_tp_getattr_hook(); this
6275 detects the absence of __getattr__ and then installs the simpler slot if
6276 necessary. */
6277
6278static PyObject *
6279slot_tp_getattro(PyObject *self, PyObject *name)
6280{
6281 PyObject *stack[1] = {name};
6282 return call_method(self, &PyId___getattribute__, stack, 1);
6283}
6284
6285static PyObject *
6286call_attribute(PyObject *self, PyObject *attr, PyObject *name)
6287{
6288 PyObject *res, *descr = NULL;
6289 descrgetfunc f = Py_TYPE(attr)->tp_descr_get;
6290
6291 if (f != NULL) {
6292 descr = f(attr, self, (PyObject *)(Py_TYPE(self)));
6293 if (descr == NULL)
6294 return NULL;
6295 else
6296 attr = descr;
6297 }
6298 res = PyObject_CallFunctionObjArgs(attr, name, NULL);
6299 Py_XDECREF(descr);
6300 return res;
6301}
6302
6303static PyObject *
6304slot_tp_getattr_hook(PyObject *self, PyObject *name)
6305{
6306 PyTypeObject *tp = Py_TYPE(self);
6307 PyObject *getattr, *getattribute, *res;
6308 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__getattr__);
6309
6310 /* speed hack: we could use lookup_maybe, but that would resolve the
6311 method fully for each attribute lookup for classes with
6312 __getattr__, even when the attribute is present. So we use
6313 _PyType_Lookup and create the method only when needed, with
6314 call_attribute. */
6315 getattr = _PyType_LookupId(tp, &PyId___getattr__);
6316 if (getattr == NULL) {
6317 /* No __getattr__ hook: use a simpler dispatcher */
6318 tp->tp_getattro = slot_tp_getattro;
6319 return slot_tp_getattro(self, name);
6320 }
6321 Py_INCREF(getattr);
6322 /* speed hack: we could use lookup_maybe, but that would resolve the
6323 method fully for each attribute lookup for classes with
6324 __getattr__, even when self has the default __getattribute__
6325 method. So we use _PyType_Lookup and create the method only when
6326 needed, with call_attribute. */
6327 getattribute = _PyType_LookupId(tp, &PyId___getattribute__);
6328 if (getattribute == NULL ||
6329 (Py_TYPE(getattribute) == &PyWrapperDescr_Type &&
6330 ((PyWrapperDescrObject *)getattribute)->d_wrapped ==
6331 (void *)PyObject_GenericGetAttr))
6332 res = PyObject_GenericGetAttr(self, name);
6333 else {
6334 Py_INCREF(getattribute);
6335 res = call_attribute(self, getattribute, name);
6336 Py_DECREF(getattribute);
6337 }
6338 if (res == NULL && PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_AttributeError)) {
6339 PyErr_Clear();
6340 res = call_attribute(self, getattr, name);
6341 }
6342 Py_DECREF(getattr);
6343 return res;
6344}

6365 return 0;

6436static PyObject *
6437slot_tp_descr_get(PyObject *self, PyObject *obj, PyObject *type)
6438{
6439 PyTypeObject *tp = Py_TYPE(self);
6440 PyObject *get;
6441 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__get__);
6442
6443 get = _PyType_LookupId(tp, &PyId___get__);
6444 if (get == NULL) {
6445 /* Avoid further slowdowns */
6446 if (tp->tp_descr_get == slot_tp_descr_get)
6447 tp->tp_descr_get = NULL;
6448 Py_INCREF(self);
6449 return self;

6451 if (obj == NULL)
6452 obj = Py_None;
6453 if (type == NULL)
6454 type = Py_None;
6455 return PyObject_CallFunctionObjArgs(get, self, obj, type, NULL);
6456}

6486 PyObject *res;
6487
6488 if (meth == NULL)
6489 return -1;

6525static void
6526slot_tp_finalize(PyObject *self)
6527{
6528 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__del__);
6529 int unbound;
6530 PyObject *del, *res;
6531 PyObject *error_type, *error_value, *error_traceback;
6532
6533 /* Save the current exception, if any. */
6534 PyErr_Fetch(&error_type, &error_value, &error_traceback);
6535
6536 /* Execute __del__ method, if any. */
6537 del = lookup_maybe_method(self, &PyId___del__, &unbound);
6538 if (del != NULL) {
6539 res = call_unbound_noarg(unbound, del, self);
6540 if (res == NULL)
6541 PyErr_WriteUnraisable(del);
6542 else
6543 Py_DECREF(res);
6544 Py_DECREF(del);
6545 }
6546
6547 /* Restore the saved exception. */
6548 PyErr_Restore(error_type, error_value, error_traceback);
6549}

6610
6611The table is ordered by offsets relative to the 'PyHeapTypeObject' structure,
6612which incorporates the additional structures used for numbers, sequences and
6613mappings. Note that multiple names may map to the same slot (e.g. __eq__,
6614__ne__ etc. all map to tp_richcompare) and one name may map to multiple slots
6615(e.g. __str__ affects tp_str as well as tp_repr). The table is terminated with
6616an all-zero entry. (This table is further initialized in init_slotdefs().)
6617*/

6856/* Given a type pointer and an offset gotten from a slotdef entry, return a
6857 pointer to the actual slot. This is not quite the same as simply adding
6858 the offset to the type pointer, since it takes care to indirect through the
6859 proper indirection pointer (as_buffer, etc.); it returns NULL if the
6860 indirection pointer is NULL. */
6861static void **
6862slotptr(PyTypeObject *type, int ioffset)
6863{
6864 char *ptr;
6865 long offset = ioffset;
6866
6867 /* Note: this depends on the order of the members of PyHeapTypeObject! */
6868 assert(offset >= 0);
6869 assert((size_t)offset < offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_buffer));
6870 if ((size_t)offset >= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_sequence)) {
6871 ptr = (char *)type->tp_as_sequence;
6872 offset -= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_sequence);
6873 }
6874 else if ((size_t)offset >= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_mapping)) {
6875 ptr = (char *)type->tp_as_mapping;
6876 offset -= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_mapping);
6877 }
6878 else if ((size_t)offset >= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_number)) {
6879 ptr = (char *)type->tp_as_number;
6880 offset -= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_number);
6881 }
6882 else if ((size_t)offset >= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_async)) {
6883 ptr = (char *)type->tp_as_async;
6884 offset -= offsetof(PyHeapTypeObject, as_async);
6885 }
6886 else {
6887 ptr = (char *)type;
6888 }
6889 if (ptr != NULL)
6890 ptr += offset;
6891 return (void **)ptr;
6892}
6893
6894/* Length of array of slotdef pointers used to store slots with the
6895 same __name__. There should be at most MAX_EQUIV-1 slotdef entries with
6896 the same __name__, for any __name__. Since that's a static property, it is
6897 appropriate to declare fixed-size arrays for this. */
6898#define MAX_EQUIV 10
6899
6900/* Return a slot pointer for a given name, but ONLY if the attribute has
6901 exactly one slot function. The name must be an interned string. */
6902static void **
6903resolve_slotdups(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *name)
6904{
6905 /* XXX Maybe this could be optimized more -- but is it worth it? */
6906
6907 /* pname and ptrs act as a little cache */
6908 static PyObject *pname;
6909 static slotdef *ptrs[MAX_EQUIV];
6910 slotdef *p, **pp;
6911 void **res, **ptr;
6912
6913 if (pname != name) {
6914 /* Collect all slotdefs that match name into ptrs. */
6915 pname = name;
6916 pp = ptrs;
6917 for (p = slotdefs; p->name_strobj; p++) {
6918 if (p->name_strobj == name)
6919 *pp++ = p;
6920 }
6921 *pp = NULL;
6922 }
6923
6924 /* Look in all matching slots of the type; if exactly one of these has
6925 a filled-in slot, return its value. Otherwise return NULL. */
6926 res = NULL;
6927 for (pp = ptrs; *pp; pp++) {
6928 ptr = slotptr(type, (*pp)->offset);
6929 if (ptr == NULL || *ptr == NULL)
6930 continue;
6931 if (res != NULL)
6932 return NULL;
6933 res = ptr;
6934 }
6935 return res;
6936}
6937
6938/* Common code for update_slots_callback() and fixup_slot_dispatchers(). This
6939 does some incredibly complex thinking and then sticks something into the
6940 slot. (It sees if the adjacent slotdefs for the same slot have conflicting
6941 interests, and then stores a generic wrapper or a specific function into
6942 the slot.) Return a pointer to the next slotdef with a different offset,
6943 because that's convenient for fixup_slot_dispatchers(). */
6944static slotdef *
6945update_one_slot(PyTypeObject *type, slotdef *p)
6946{
6947 PyObject *descr;
6948 PyWrapperDescrObject *d;
6949 void *generic = NULL, *specific = NULL;
6950 int use_generic = 0;
6951 int offset = p->offset;
6952 void **ptr = slotptr(type, offset);
6953
6954 if (ptr == NULL) {
6955 do {
6956 ++p;
6957 } while (p->offset == offset);
6958 return p;
6959 }
6960 do {
6961 descr = _PyType_Lookup(type, p->name_strobj);
6962 if (descr == NULL) {
6963 if (ptr == (void**)&type->tp_iternext) {
6964 specific = (void *)_PyObject_NextNotImplemented;
6965 }
6966 continue;
6967 }
6968 if (Py_TYPE(descr) == &PyWrapperDescr_Type &&
6969 ((PyWrapperDescrObject *)descr)->d_base->name_strobj == p->name_strobj) {
6970 void **tptr = resolve_slotdups(type, p->name_strobj);
6971 if (tptr == NULL || tptr == ptr)
6972 generic = p->function;
6973 d = (PyWrapperDescrObject *)descr;
6974 if (d->d_base->wrapper == p->wrapper &&
6975 PyType_IsSubtype(type, PyDescr_TYPE(d)))
6976 {
6977 if (specific == NULL ||
6978 specific == d->d_wrapped)
6979 specific = d->d_wrapped;
6980 else
6981 use_generic = 1;
6982 }
6983 }
6984 else if (Py_TYPE(descr) == &PyCFunction_Type &&
6985 PyCFunction_GET_FUNCTION(descr) ==
6986 (PyCFunction)tp_new_wrapper &&
6987 ptr == (void**)&type->tp_new)
6988 {
6989 /* The __new__ wrapper is not a wrapper descriptor,
6990 so must be special-cased differently.
6991 If we don't do this, creating an instance will
6992 always use slot_tp_new which will look up
6993 __new__ in the MRO which will call tp_new_wrapper
6994 which will look through the base classes looking
6995 for a static base and call its tp_new (usually
6996 PyType_GenericNew), after performing various
6997 sanity checks and constructing a new argument
6998 list. Cut all that nonsense short -- this speeds
6999 up instance creation tremendously. */
7000 specific = (void *)type->tp_new;
7001 /* XXX I'm not 100% sure that there isn't a hole
7002 in this reasoning that requires additional
7003 sanity checks. I'll buy the first person to
7004 point out a bug in this reasoning a beer. */
7005 }
7006 else if (descr == Py_None &&
7007 ptr == (void**)&type->tp_hash) {
7008 /* We specifically allow __hash__ to be set to None
7009 to prevent inheritance of the default
7010 implementation from object.__hash__ */
7011 specific = (void *)PyObject_HashNotImplemented;
7012 }
7013 else {
7014 use_generic = 1;
7015 generic = p->function;
7016 }
7017 } while ((++p)->offset == offset);
7018 if (specific && !use_generic)
7019 *ptr = specific;
7020 else
7021 *ptr = generic;
7022 return p;
7023}
7024
7025/* In the type, update the slots whose slotdefs are gathered in the pp array.
7026 This is a callback for update_subclasses(). */
7027static int
7028update_slots_callback(PyTypeObject *type, void *data)
7029{
7030 slotdef **pp = (slotdef **)data;
7031
7032 for (; *pp; pp++)
7033 update_one_slot(type, *pp);
7034 return 0;
7035}
7036
7037static int slotdefs_initialized = 0;
7038/* Initialize the slotdefs table by adding interned string objects for the
7039 names. */
7040static void
7041init_slotdefs(void)
7042{
7043 slotdef *p;
7044
7045 if (slotdefs_initialized)
7046 return;
7047 for (p = slotdefs; p->name; p++) {
7048 /* Slots must be ordered by their offset in the PyHeapTypeObject. */
7049 assert(!p[1].name || p->offset <= p[1].offset);
7050 p->name_strobj = PyUnicode_InternFromString(p->name);
7051 if (!p->name_strobj || !PyUnicode_CHECK_INTERNED(p->name_strobj))
7052 Py_FatalError("Out of memory interning slotdef names");
7053 }
7054 slotdefs_initialized = 1;
7055}
7056
7057/* Undo init_slotdefs, releasing the interned strings. */
7058static void clear_slotdefs(void)
7059{
7060 slotdef *p;
7061 for (p = slotdefs; p->name; p++) {
7062 Py_CLEAR(p->name_strobj);
7063 }
7064 slotdefs_initialized = 0;
7065}
7066
7067/* Update the slots after assignment to a class (type) attribute. */
7068static int
7069update_slot(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *name)
7070{
7071 slotdef *ptrs[MAX_EQUIV];
7072 slotdef *p;
7073 slotdef **pp;
7074 int offset;
7075
7076 assert(PyUnicode_CheckExact(name));
7077 assert(PyUnicode_CHECK_INTERNED(name));
7078
7079 /* Clear the VALID_VERSION flag of 'type' and all its
7080 subclasses. This could possibly be unified with the
7081 update_subclasses() recursion below, but carefully:
7082 they each have their own conditions on which to stop
7083 recursing into subclasses. */
7084 PyType_Modified(type);
7085
7086 init_slotdefs();
7087 pp = ptrs;
7088 for (p = slotdefs; p->name; p++) {
7089 if (p->name_strobj == name)
7090 *pp++ = p;
7091 }
7092 *pp = NULL;
7093 for (pp = ptrs; *pp; pp++) {
7094 p = *pp;
7095 offset = p->offset;
7096 while (p > slotdefs && (p-1)->offset == offset)
7097 --p;
7098 *pp = p;
7099 }
7100 if (ptrs[0] == NULL)
7101 return 0; /* Not an attribute that affects any slots */
7102 return update_subclasses(type, name,
7103 update_slots_callback, (void *)ptrs);
7104}
7105
7106/* Store the proper functions in the slot dispatches at class (type)
7107 definition time, based upon which operations the class overrides in its
7108 dict. */
7109static void
7110fixup_slot_dispatchers(PyTypeObject *type)
7111{
7112 slotdef *p;
7113
7114 init_slotdefs();
7115 for (p = slotdefs; p->name; )
7116 p = update_one_slot(type, p);
7117}
7118
7119static void
7120update_all_slots(PyTypeObject* type)
7121{
7122 slotdef *p;
7123
7124 init_slotdefs();
7125 for (p = slotdefs; p->name; p++) {
7126 /* update_slot returns int but can't actually fail */
7127 update_slot(type, p->name_strobj);
7128 }
7129}
