7131/* Call __set_name__ on all descriptors in a newly generated type */
7132static int
7133set_names(PyTypeObject *type)
7134{
7135 PyObject *names_to_set, *key, *value, *set_name, *tmp;
7136 Py_ssize_t i = 0;
7137
7138 names_to_set = PyDict_Copy(type->tp_dict);
7139 if (names_to_set == NULL)
7140 return -1;
7141
7142 while (PyDict_Next(names_to_set, &i, &key, &value)) {
7143 set_name = _PyObject_LookupSpecial(value, &PyId___set_name__);
7144 if (set_name != NULL) {
7145 tmp = PyObject_CallFunctionObjArgs(set_name, type, key, NULL);
7146 Py_DECREF(set_name);
7147 if (tmp == NULL) {
7148 _PyErr_FormatFromCause(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7149 "Error calling __set_name__ on '%.100s' instance %R "
7150 "in '%.100s'",
7151 value->ob_type->tp_name, key, type->tp_name);
7152 Py_DECREF(names_to_set);
7153 return -1;
7154 }
7155 else
7156 Py_DECREF(tmp);
7157 }
7158 else if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
7159 Py_DECREF(names_to_set);
7160 return -1;
7161 }
7162 }
7163
7164 Py_DECREF(names_to_set);
7165 return 0;
7166}
7167
7168/* Call __init_subclass__ on the parent of a newly generated type */
7169static int
7170init_subclass(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *kwds)
7171{
7172 PyObject *super, *func, *result;
7173 PyObject *args[2] = {(PyObject *)type, (PyObject *)type};
7174
7175 super = _PyObject_FastCall((PyObject *)&PySuper_Type, args, 2);
7176 if (super == NULL) {
7177 return -1;
7178 }
7179
7180 func = _PyObject_GetAttrId(super, &PyId___init_subclass__);
7181 Py_DECREF(super);
7182 if (func == NULL) {
7183 return -1;
7184 }
7185
7186
7187 result = _PyObject_FastCallDict(func, NULL, 0, kwds);
7188 Py_DECREF(func);
7189 if (result == NULL) {
7190 return -1;
7191 }
7192
7193 Py_DECREF(result);
7194 return 0;
7195}
7196
7197/* recurse_down_subclasses() and update_subclasses() are mutually
7198 recursive functions to call a callback for all subclasses,
7199 but refraining from recursing into subclasses that define 'name'. */
7200
7201static int
7202update_subclasses(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *name,
7203 update_callback callback, void *data)
7204{
7205 if (callback(type, data) < 0)
7206 return -1;
7207 return recurse_down_subclasses(type, name, callback, data);
7208}
7209
7210static int
7211recurse_down_subclasses(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *name,
7212 update_callback callback, void *data)
7213{
7214 PyTypeObject *subclass;
7215 PyObject *ref, *subclasses, *dict;
7216 Py_ssize_t i;
7217
7218 subclasses = type->tp_subclasses;
7219 if (subclasses == NULL)
7220 return 0;
7221 assert(PyDict_CheckExact(subclasses));
7222 i = 0;
7223 while (PyDict_Next(subclasses, &i, NULL, &ref)) {
7224 assert(PyWeakref_CheckRef(ref));
7225 subclass = (PyTypeObject *)PyWeakref_GET_OBJECT(ref);
7226 assert(subclass != NULL);
7227 if ((PyObject *)subclass == Py_None)
7228 continue;
7229 assert(PyType_Check(subclass));
7230 /* Avoid recursing down into unaffected classes */
7231 dict = subclass->tp_dict;
7232 if (dict != NULL && PyDict_Check(dict) &&
7233 PyDict_GetItem(dict, name) != NULL)
7234 continue;
7235 if (update_subclasses(subclass, name, callback, data) < 0)
7236 return -1;
7237 }
7238 return 0;
7239}
7240
7241/* This function is called by PyType_Ready() to populate the type's
7242 dictionary with method descriptors for function slots. For each
7243 function slot (like tp_repr) that's defined in the type, one or more
7244 corresponding descriptors are added in the type's tp_dict dictionary
7245 under the appropriate name (like __repr__). Some function slots
7246 cause more than one descriptor to be added (for example, the nb_add
7247 slot adds both __add__ and __radd__ descriptors) and some function
7248 slots compete for the same descriptor (for example both sq_item and
7249 mp_subscript generate a __getitem__ descriptor).
7250
7251 In the latter case, the first slotdef entry encountered wins. Since
7252 slotdef entries are sorted by the offset of the slot in the
7253 PyHeapTypeObject, this gives us some control over disambiguating
7254 between competing slots: the members of PyHeapTypeObject are listed
7255 from most general to least general, so the most general slot is
7256 preferred. In particular, because as_mapping comes before as_sequence,
7257 for a type that defines both mp_subscript and sq_item, mp_subscript
7258 wins.
7259
7260 This only adds new descriptors and doesn't overwrite entries in
7261 tp_dict that were previously defined. The descriptors contain a
7262 reference to the C function they must call, so that it's safe if they
7263 are copied into a subtype's __dict__ and the subtype has a different
7264 C function in its slot -- calling the method defined by the
7265 descriptor will call the C function that was used to create it,
7266 rather than the C function present in the slot when it is called.
7267 (This is important because a subtype may have a C function in the
7268 slot that calls the method from the dictionary, and we want to avoid
7269 infinite recursion here.) */
7270
7271static int
7272add_operators(PyTypeObject *type)
7273{
7274 PyObject *dict = type->tp_dict;
7275 slotdef *p;
7276 PyObject *descr;
7277 void **ptr;
7278
7279 init_slotdefs();
7280 for (p = slotdefs; p->name; p++) {
7281 if (p->wrapper == NULL)
7282 continue;
7283 ptr = slotptr(type, p->offset);
7284 if (!ptr || !*ptr)
7285 continue;
7286 if (PyDict_GetItem(dict, p->name_strobj))
7287 continue;
7288 if (*ptr == (void *)PyObject_HashNotImplemented) {
7289 /* Classes may prevent the inheritance of the tp_hash
7290 slot by storing PyObject_HashNotImplemented in it. Make it
7291 visible as a None value for the __hash__ attribute. */
7292 if (PyDict_SetItem(dict, p->name_strobj, Py_None) < 0)
7293 return -1;
7294 }
7295 else {
7296 descr = PyDescr_NewWrapper(type, p, *ptr);
7297 if (descr == NULL)
7298 return -1;
7299 if (PyDict_SetItem(dict, p->name_strobj, descr) < 0) {
7300 Py_DECREF(descr);
7301 return -1;
7302 }
7303 Py_DECREF(descr);
7304 }
7305 }
7306 if (type->tp_new != NULL) {
7307 if (add_tp_new_wrapper(type) < 0)
7308 return -1;
7309 }
7310 return 0;
7311}

7346super_repr(PyObject *self)
7347{

7350 if (su->obj_type)
7351 return PyUnicode_FromFormat(
7352 "<super: <class '%s'>, <%s object>>",
7353 su->type ? su->type->tp_name : "NULL",

7360
7361static PyObject *
7362super_getattro(PyObject *self, PyObject *name)
7363{
7364 superobject *su = (superobject *)self;
7365 PyTypeObject *starttype;
7366 PyObject *mro;
7367 Py_ssize_t i, n;
7368
7369 starttype = su->obj_type;
7370 if (starttype == NULL)
7371 goto skip;
7372
7373 /* We want __class__ to return the class of the super object
7374 (i.e. super, or a subclass), not the class of su->obj. */
7375 if (PyUnicode_Check(name) &&
7376 PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(name) == 9 &&
7377 _PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(name, &PyId___class__))
7378 goto skip;
7379
7380 mro = starttype->tp_mro;
7381 if (mro == NULL)
7382 goto skip;
7383
7384 assert(PyTuple_Check(mro));
7385 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(mro);
7386
7387 /* No need to check the last one: it's gonna be skipped anyway. */
7388 for (i = 0; i+1 < n; i++) {
7389 if ((PyObject *)(su->type) == PyTuple_GET_ITEM(mro, i))
7390 break;
7391 }
7392 i++; /* skip su->type (if any) */
7393 if (i >= n)
7394 goto skip;
7395
7396 /* keep a strong reference to mro because starttype->tp_mro can be
7397 replaced during PyDict_GetItem(dict, name) */
7398 Py_INCREF(mro);
7399 do {
7400 PyObject *res, *tmp, *dict;
7401 descrgetfunc f;
7402
7403 tmp = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(mro, i);
7404 assert(PyType_Check(tmp));
7405
7406 dict = ((PyTypeObject *)tmp)->tp_dict;
7407 assert(dict != NULL && PyDict_Check(dict));
7408
7409 res = PyDict_GetItem(dict, name);
7410 if (res != NULL) {
7411 Py_INCREF(res);
7412
7413 f = Py_TYPE(res)->tp_descr_get;
7414 if (f != NULL) {
7415 tmp = f(res,
7416 /* Only pass 'obj' param if this is instance-mode super
7417 (See SF ID #743627) */
7418 (su->obj == (PyObject *)starttype) ? NULL : su->obj,
7419 (PyObject *)starttype);
7420 Py_DECREF(res);
7421 res = tmp;
7422 }
7423
7424 Py_DECREF(mro);
7425 return res;
7426 }
7427
7428 i++;
7429 } while (i < n);
7430 Py_DECREF(mro);
7431
7432 skip:
7433 return PyObject_GenericGetAttr(self, name);
7434}
7435
7436static PyTypeObject *
7437supercheck(PyTypeObject *type, PyObject *obj)
7438{
7439 /* Check that a super() call makes sense. Return a type object.
7440
7441 obj can be a class, or an instance of one:
7442
7443 - If it is a class, it must be a subclass of 'type'. This case is
7444 used for class methods; the return value is obj.
7445
7446 - If it is an instance, it must be an instance of 'type'. This is
7447 the normal case; the return value is obj.__class__.
7448
7449 But... when obj is an instance, we want to allow for the case where
7450 Py_TYPE(obj) is not a subclass of type, but obj.__class__ is!
7451 This will allow using super() with a proxy for obj.
7452 */
7453
7454 /* Check for first bullet above (special case) */
7455 if (PyType_Check(obj) && PyType_IsSubtype((PyTypeObject *)obj, type)) {
7456 Py_INCREF(obj);
7457 return (PyTypeObject *)obj;
7458 }
7459
7460 /* Normal case */
7461 if (PyType_IsSubtype(Py_TYPE(obj), type)) {
7462 Py_INCREF(Py_TYPE(obj));
7463 return Py_TYPE(obj);
7464 }
7465 else {
7466 /* Try the slow way */
7467 PyObject *class_attr;
7468
7469 class_attr = _PyObject_GetAttrId(obj, &PyId___class__);
7470 if (class_attr != NULL &&
7471 PyType_Check(class_attr) &&
7472 (PyTypeObject *)class_attr != Py_TYPE(obj))
7473 {
7474 int ok = PyType_IsSubtype(
7475 (PyTypeObject *)class_attr, type);
7476 if (ok)
7477 return (PyTypeObject *)class_attr;
7478 }
7479
7480 if (class_attr == NULL)
7481 PyErr_Clear();
7482 else
7483 Py_DECREF(class_attr);
7484 }
7485
7486 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError,
7487 "super(type, obj): "
7488 "obj must be an instance or subtype of type");
7489 return NULL;
7490}
7491
7492static PyObject *
7493super_descr_get(PyObject *self, PyObject *obj, PyObject *type)
7494{
7495 superobject *su = (superobject *)self;
7496 superobject *newobj;
7497
7498 if (obj == NULL || obj == Py_None || su->obj != NULL) {
7499 /* Not binding to an object, or already bound */
7500 Py_INCREF(self);
7501 return self;
7502 }
7503 if (Py_TYPE(su) != &PySuper_Type)
7504 /* If su is an instance of a (strict) subclass of super,
7505 call its type */
7506 return PyObject_CallFunctionObjArgs((PyObject *)Py_TYPE(su),
7507 su->type, obj, NULL);
7508 else {
7509 /* Inline the common case */
7510 PyTypeObject *obj_type = supercheck(su->type, obj);
7511 if (obj_type == NULL)
7512 return NULL;
7513 newobj = (superobject *)PySuper_Type.tp_new(&PySuper_Type,
7514 NULL, NULL);
7515 if (newobj == NULL)
7516 return NULL;
7517 Py_INCREF(su->type);
7518 Py_INCREF(obj);
7519 newobj->type = su->type;
7520 newobj->obj = obj;
7521 newobj->obj_type = obj_type;
7522 return (PyObject *)newobj;
7523 }
7524}
7525
7526static int
7527super_init(PyObject *self, PyObject *args, PyObject *kwds)
7528{
7529 superobject *su = (superobject *)self;
7530 PyTypeObject *type = NULL;
7531 PyObject *obj = NULL;
7532 PyTypeObject *obj_type = NULL;
7533
7534 if (!_PyArg_NoKeywords("super", kwds))
7535 return -1;
7536 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "|O!O:super", &PyType_Type, &type, &obj))
7537 return -1;
7538
7539 if (type == NULL) {
7540 /* Call super(), without args -- fill in from __class__
7541 and first local variable on the stack. */
7542 PyFrameObject *f;
7543 PyCodeObject *co;
7544 Py_ssize_t i, n;
7545 f = PyThreadState_GET()->frame;
7546 if (f == NULL) {
7547 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7548 "super(): no current frame");
7549 return -1;
7550 }
7551 co = f->f_code;
7552 if (co == NULL) {
7553 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7554 "super(): no code object");
7555 return -1;
7556 }
7557 if (co->co_argcount == 0) {
7558 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7559 "super(): no arguments");
7560 return -1;
7561 }
7562 obj = f->f_localsplus[0];
7563 if (obj == NULL && co->co_cell2arg) {
7564 /* The first argument might be a cell. */
7565 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(co->co_cellvars);
7566 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
7567 if (co->co_cell2arg[i] == 0) {
7568 PyObject *cell = f->f_localsplus[co->co_nlocals + i];
7569 assert(PyCell_Check(cell));
7570 obj = PyCell_GET(cell);
7571 break;
7572 }
7573 }
7574 }
7575 if (obj == NULL) {
7576 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7577 "super(): arg[0] deleted");
7578 return -1;
7579 }
7580 if (co->co_freevars == NULL)
7581 n = 0;
7582 else {
7583 assert(PyTuple_Check(co->co_freevars));
7584 n = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(co->co_freevars);
7585 }
7586 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
7587 PyObject *name = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(co->co_freevars, i);
7588 assert(PyUnicode_Check(name));
7589 if (_PyUnicode_EqualToASCIIId(name, &PyId___class__)) {
7590 Py_ssize_t index = co->co_nlocals +
7591 PyTuple_GET_SIZE(co->co_cellvars) + i;
7592 PyObject *cell = f->f_localsplus[index];
7593 if (cell == NULL || !PyCell_Check(cell)) {
7594 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7595 "super(): bad __class__ cell");
7596 return -1;
7597 }
7598 type = (PyTypeObject *) PyCell_GET(cell);
7599 if (type == NULL) {
7600 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7601 "super(): empty __class__ cell");
7602 return -1;
7603 }
7604 if (!PyType_Check(type)) {
7605 PyErr_Format(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7606 "super(): __class__ is not a type (%s)",
7607 Py_TYPE(type)->tp_name);
7608 return -1;
7609 }
7610 break;
7611 }
7612 }
7613 if (type == NULL) {
7614 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
7615 "super(): __class__ cell not found");
7616 return -1;
7617 }
7618 }
7619
7620 if (obj == Py_None)
7621 obj = NULL;
7622 if (obj != NULL) {
7623 obj_type = supercheck(type, obj);
7624 if (obj_type == NULL)
7625 return -1;
7626 Py_INCREF(obj);
7627 }
7628 Py_INCREF(type);
7629 Py_XSETREF(su->type, type);
7630 Py_XSETREF(su->obj, obj);
7631 Py_XSETREF(su->obj_type, obj_type);
7632 return 0;
7633}

7635PyDoc_STRVAR(super_doc,
7636"super() -> same as super(__class__, <first argument>)\n"
7637"super(type) -> unbound super object\n"
7638"super(type, obj) -> bound super object; requires isinstance(obj, type)\n"
7639"super(type, type2) -> bound super object; requires issubclass(type2, type)\n"
7640"Typical use to call a cooperative superclass method:\n"
7641"class C(B):\n"
7642" def meth(self, arg):\n"
7643" super().meth(arg)\n"
7644"This works for class methods too:\n"
7645"class C(B):\n"
7646" @classmethod\n"
7647" def cmeth(cls, arg):\n"
7648" super().cmeth(arg)\n");

7653 superobject *su = (superobject *)self;
7654
7655 Py_VISIT(su->obj);
7656 Py_VISIT(su->type);
7657 Py_VISIT(su->obj_type);
7658
7659 return 0;
7660}
